1
00:00:43,451 --> 00:00:45,748
Hey, buddy.

2
00:00:45,783 --> 00:00:47,783
You don't waste time, do you?

3
00:00:47,818 --> 00:00:49,482
I try not to.

4
00:00:49,517 --> 00:00:50,817
Well, you need help?

5
00:00:50,852 --> 00:00:51,917
Sure.

6
00:00:55,651 --> 00:00:57,717
Would you like to tell us

7
00:00:57,752 --> 00:00:59,783
what the hell that was all about?

8
00:00:59,818 --> 00:01:01,115
I don't like good-byes.

9
00:01:01,150 --> 00:01:03,983
Kind of the point of
a good-bye party, John.

10
00:01:04,018 --> 00:01:06,534
Went to a certain amount
of trouble, you know?

11
00:01:06,569 --> 00:01:09,015
Could've at least stayed
a few minutes, huh?

12
00:01:09,050 --> 00:01:12,950
Eaten some of the food
we so feverishly prepared?

13
00:01:12,985 --> 00:01:14,549
I apologize, Harry.

14
00:01:14,584 --> 00:01:16,149
But why are you moving so quickly?

15
00:01:16,184 --> 00:01:18,284
You only resigned a couple of days ago.

16
00:01:18,319 --> 00:01:20,384
You got the history chair at Stanford.

17
00:01:20,419 --> 00:01:21,482
I wish.

18
00:01:21,517 --> 00:01:23,683
Well, taquitos, chicken wings,

19
00:01:23,718 --> 00:01:25,567
Roastie-Toasties and beer.

20
00:01:25,602 --> 00:01:27,382
If we'd had more time,

21
00:01:27,417 --> 00:01:29,451
we'd have done something
a little more grandiose.

22
00:01:29,486 --> 00:01:31,217
Candlelight dinner at McDonald's.

23
00:01:31,252 --> 00:01:32,782
Strippers.

24
00:01:32,817 --> 00:01:34,618
Taquitos are fine.

25
00:01:34,653 --> 00:01:36,549
A'right.

26
00:01:36,584 --> 00:01:38,349
Art's gonna be along, too.

27
00:01:38,384 --> 00:01:40,150
He's, uh, talking to a student. Pfft.

28
00:01:40,185 --> 00:01:42,049
Is George taking over for you?

29
00:01:42,084 --> 00:01:44,750
- George or Trimbell.
- Has the dean made up his mind?

30
00:01:44,785 --> 00:01:45,850
He hasn't called.

31
00:01:45,885 --> 00:01:46,882
My god!

32
00:01:46,917 --> 00:01:48,316
Wh-What is this?

33
00:01:48,351 --> 00:01:49,616
It looks like a Van Gogh,

34
00:01:49,651 --> 00:01:51,101
But I've never seen it before.

35
00:01:51,136 --> 00:01:52,516
Is that an original, John?

36
00:01:52,551 --> 00:01:54,883
No, it's just a gift someone gave me.

37
00:01:54,918 --> 00:01:56,867
Still, it's a superb copy.

38
00:01:56,902 --> 00:01:58,826
Contemporaneous, I think,

39
00:01:58,861 --> 00:02:00,750
May I take a closer look?

40
00:02:00,785 --> 00:02:01,883
Please, yeah.

41
00:02:04,084 --> 00:02:06,684
Yeah, it's the same
stretcher as Van Gogh used.

42
00:02:06,719 --> 00:02:09,284
Yeah, there's writing
on the back in French.

43
00:02:09,319 --> 00:02:11,718
Oh, "to my friend Jacques Borne."

44
00:02:11,753 --> 00:02:12,949
Wonder who that was?

45
00:02:12,984 --> 00:02:14,449
Someone he knew, I guess.

46
00:02:14,484 --> 00:02:16,149
Brilliant deduction, sherlock.

47
00:02:16,184 --> 00:02:19,084
Surely you'll have this
looked at, appraised?

48
00:02:19,119 --> 00:02:21,082
Well, maybe sometime,

49
00:02:21,117 --> 00:02:24,351
but I wouldn't really want money for it.

50
00:02:25,850 --> 00:02:28,049
That does it.

51
00:02:28,084 --> 00:02:29,915
Put that stuff in the kitchen.

52
00:02:29,950 --> 00:02:33,451
No, I'm gonna put it
in the bathroom, John.

53
00:02:33,486 --> 00:02:35,718
Gas is off, electricity's on.

54
00:02:37,417 --> 00:02:38,949
Get comfortable while you can.

55
00:02:38,984 --> 00:02:41,484
The furniture's going this afternoon.

56
00:02:41,519 --> 00:02:43,984
It's been years since I sat on a floor.

57
00:02:44,019 --> 00:02:45,934
Heh. I can't remember her name.

58
00:02:45,969 --> 00:02:47,576
Eh, it's good for the back.

59
00:02:47,611 --> 00:02:49,464
Can we do yoga exercises?

60
00:02:49,499 --> 00:02:51,317
Tantric yoga, we can.

61
00:02:52,684 --> 00:02:55,284
So you're leaving
good old "we teach you."

62
00:02:55,319 --> 00:02:58,351
Rather suddenly, you must admit.

63
00:02:58,386 --> 00:03:00,035
Truth time, John.

64
00:03:00,070 --> 00:03:01,684
Is there a problem?

65
00:03:01,719 --> 00:03:03,049
No.

66
00:03:03,084 --> 00:03:05,267
Oh, come on, you know we wanna help.

67
00:03:05,302 --> 00:03:07,451
That's appreciated, but really -

68
00:03:07,486 --> 00:03:09,485
There's no problem.

69
00:03:09,520 --> 00:03:11,102
Well, now I am curious.

70
00:03:11,137 --> 00:03:12,410
Where are you going?

71
00:03:12,445 --> 00:03:13,649
Givin' up tenure...

72
00:03:13,684 --> 00:03:15,649
A decade of professorship,

73
00:03:15,684 --> 00:03:18,082
in line to chair the department,

74
00:03:18,117 --> 00:03:20,950
and you don't know where you're going?

75
00:03:20,985 --> 00:03:22,416
Call it cabin fever.

76
00:03:22,451 --> 00:03:24,950
After a while, I get itchy feet.

77
00:03:24,985 --> 00:03:26,249
I've done this before.

78
00:03:26,284 --> 00:03:29,351
No, no, no, you're too young
to have done this before.

79
00:03:29,386 --> 00:03:31,651
And he hasn't aged a day in ten years.

80
00:03:31,686 --> 00:03:33,182
Every woman on the faculty

81
00:03:33,217 --> 00:03:35,783
would give anything to have that secret.

82
00:03:35,818 --> 00:03:37,384
Is that what they're after, Edith?

83
00:03:37,419 --> 00:03:39,050
Oh, stop, Harry.

84
00:03:41,883 --> 00:03:43,451
Wow, can you pull this?

85
00:03:45,184 --> 00:03:46,467
What the hell?

86
00:03:46,502 --> 00:03:47,793
What do you hunt?

87
00:03:47,828 --> 00:03:49,039
Deer, mostly.

88
00:03:49,074 --> 00:03:50,216
Around big bear.

89
00:03:50,251 --> 00:03:51,616
With a bow and arrow?

90
00:03:51,651 --> 00:03:53,382
Most people can't bag a deer

91
00:03:53,417 --> 00:03:55,417
with a rifle and a telescopic sight.

92
00:03:55,452 --> 00:03:57,035
Though, good eatin'.

93
00:03:57,070 --> 00:03:58,583
The best wild game.

94
00:03:58,618 --> 00:04:00,184
Lives naturally, eats naturally.

95
00:04:00,219 --> 00:04:01,750
Well, it's beautiful.

96
00:04:04,885 --> 00:04:06,584
Art.

97
00:04:08,284 --> 00:04:09,915
Ah.

98
00:04:09,950 --> 00:04:13,217
So, can I get an "a" for awesome?

99
00:04:13,252 --> 00:04:14,268
Oh, my gosh.

100
00:04:15,561 --> 00:04:17,039
That was fun.

101
00:04:17,074 --> 00:04:18,482
Hey, John.

102
00:04:18,517 --> 00:04:20,950
You know Linda.
You had her last semester.

103
00:04:20,985 --> 00:04:22,316
Hi. Hey.

104
00:04:22,351 --> 00:04:24,250
She's one of my victims now.
I'm taking her home.

105
00:04:24,285 --> 00:04:26,150
She wanted to come by
and say hello good-bye.

106
00:04:26,185 --> 00:04:27,617
Is Art as tough as I hear?

107
00:04:27,652 --> 00:04:29,015
Oh, archaeology's tough.

108
00:04:29,050 --> 00:04:31,050
Dr. Jenkins is a fine teacher.

109
00:04:31,085 --> 00:04:33,050
Oh, that's very politic.

110
00:04:33,085 --> 00:04:34,616
It's very true. Uh-huh.

111
00:04:34,651 --> 00:04:37,115
Something for you to
read on the road, pal.

112
00:04:37,150 --> 00:04:40,050
<i>"Shadows of the cave:
parallels to early man."</i>

113
00:04:40,085 --> 00:04:41,484
M. Jenkins.

114
00:04:41,519 --> 00:04:42,701
Publish or perish.

115
00:04:42,736 --> 00:04:43,848
I'd rather read

116
00:04:43,883 --> 00:04:44,950
than write another one.

117
00:04:44,985 --> 00:04:46,883
Thank you.

118
00:04:46,918 --> 00:04:48,149
Hi.

119
00:04:48,184 --> 00:04:50,434
Oh, everybody, this is Linda.

120
00:04:50,469 --> 00:04:52,684
Linda, this is everybody.

121
00:04:52,719 --> 00:04:54,251
Linda. Hi.

122
00:04:54,286 --> 00:04:56,516
So.

123
00:04:56,551 --> 00:04:59,050
Where you going, John,
like we give a damn?

124
00:04:59,085 --> 00:05:00,251
We've already covered that.

125
00:05:00,286 --> 00:05:02,715
John's got itchy feet.

126
00:05:02,750 --> 00:05:05,050
There are over-the-counter
remedies for that, John.

127
00:05:07,984 --> 00:05:09,317
So there is a problem.

128
00:05:09,352 --> 00:05:11,115
No.

129
00:05:11,150 --> 00:05:13,451
I just like to move on now and then.

130
00:05:13,486 --> 00:05:14,817
It's a personal thing.

131
00:05:16,284 --> 00:05:18,284
Well, not to pry.

132
00:05:25,850 --> 00:05:28,715
I'm sorry I don't
have more to offer you.

133
00:05:28,750 --> 00:05:31,284
Got conversation, some
seats for your behinds,

134
00:05:31,319 --> 00:05:32,351
And, uh...

135
00:05:36,117 --> 00:05:38,618
Is he ducking out on us again?

136
00:05:40,050 --> 00:05:41,715
...I do have this.

137
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:46,382
Oh ho ho! Johnny Walker green!

138
00:05:46,417 --> 00:05:49,184
Didn't even
know they made it in green.

139
00:05:49,219 --> 00:05:50,649
What do they pay you?

140
00:05:50,684 --> 00:05:52,616
Nothing is too good for my friends.

141
00:05:52,651 --> 00:05:55,618
But I'm sorry -
we are down to plastic cups now.

142
00:05:55,653 --> 00:05:57,618
That's a sacrilege I'll tolerate.

143
00:05:57,653 --> 00:05:59,301
I will do the honors.

144
00:05:59,336 --> 00:06:00,950
Oh, come to papa.

145
00:06:02,551 --> 00:06:04,050
Ooh! Here, cups, cups.

146
00:06:04,085 --> 00:06:05,117
There we go.

147
00:06:05,152 --> 00:06:06,251
Step on in here.

148
00:06:06,286 --> 00:06:07,316
There ya go...

149
00:06:07,351 --> 00:06:09,817
One for the birthday boy
- Excuse me. Art?

150
00:06:09,852 --> 00:06:10,949
No, not for me.

151
00:06:10,984 --> 00:06:12,349
Oh, no, I don't drink.

152
00:06:12,384 --> 00:06:14,417
We're not
gonna card you, darling.

153
00:06:14,452 --> 00:06:16,451
All right, here, join
the circle at least.

154
00:06:16,486 --> 00:06:21,150
Well, to long life and good fortune

155
00:06:21,185 --> 00:06:22,715
To our esteemed friend

156
00:06:22,750 --> 00:06:24,667
and colleague, John Oldman.

157
00:06:24,702 --> 00:06:26,584
May he find undeserved bliss

158
00:06:26,619 --> 00:06:27,817
wherever he goes.

159
00:06:27,852 --> 00:06:28,815
Hear, hear.

160
00:06:28,850 --> 00:06:30,734
<i>Skol. Na zdorovye.</i>

161
00:06:30,769 --> 00:06:32,618
One off the top, John.

162
00:06:37,718 --> 00:06:39,451
Mm! Oh, that's good.

163
00:06:39,486 --> 00:06:40,651
Excuse me.

164
00:06:42,883 --> 00:06:46,251
John, we're all sorry to see you go.

165
00:06:46,286 --> 00:06:47,351
Truly.

166
00:06:49,850 --> 00:06:51,949
Okay. Now we're done with that,

167
00:06:51,984 --> 00:06:53,984
what do we do for the
rest of the afternoon?

168
00:06:54,019 --> 00:06:55,801
Anyone got a good topic?

169
00:06:55,836 --> 00:06:57,584
Like this, maybe? Heh.

170
00:06:57,619 --> 00:06:58,616
What is that?

171
00:06:58,651 --> 00:07:01,384
It's a burin off a parrot beak.

172
00:07:01,419 --> 00:07:03,234
Inclined chisel point...

173
00:07:03,269 --> 00:07:05,293
Probably early Magdalenian.

174
00:07:05,328 --> 00:07:07,317
May I see that?
Sure.

175
00:07:13,417 --> 00:07:15,150
Yes indeed, that's what it is.

176
00:07:16,384 --> 00:07:17,583
What's a burin?

177
00:07:17,618 --> 00:07:19,249
A burin is a flint tool

178
00:07:19,284 --> 00:07:21,883
for grooving wood and
bone, antlers especially,

179
00:07:21,918 --> 00:07:24,382
to make spear and harpoon points.

180
00:07:24,417 --> 00:07:26,417
Magdalenians weren't
noted for flint work,

181
00:07:26,452 --> 00:07:28,184
so this is a very nice specimen.

182
00:07:28,219 --> 00:07:30,684
Okay, what's a Magdalenian?

183
00:07:30,719 --> 00:07:32,115
A later Cro-Magnon,

184
00:07:32,150 --> 00:07:33,449
without gettin' technical.

185
00:07:33,484 --> 00:07:36,618
It's the final culture
of the upper Paleolithic.

186
00:07:36,653 --> 00:07:38,435
If stones could speak, eh, Art?

187
00:07:38,470 --> 00:07:40,182
So where'd you get that, John?

188
00:07:40,217 --> 00:07:42,783
Believe it or not, from a thrift shop.
A quarter.

189
00:07:42,818 --> 00:07:44,349
You lucky dog!

190
00:07:44,384 --> 00:07:46,651
I gotta go digging
for this kind of stuff.

191
00:07:46,686 --> 00:07:47,883
Can I, uh...?

192
00:07:47,918 --> 00:07:48,917
Yeah.

193
00:07:52,317 --> 00:07:53,451
Huh.

194
00:07:58,484 --> 00:08:00,182
Maybe...

195
00:08:00,217 --> 00:08:01,782
I'm glad you did this.

196
00:08:01,817 --> 00:08:04,618
Did what? You mean come over?

197
00:08:04,653 --> 00:08:06,349
Maybe?

198
00:08:06,384 --> 00:08:07,667
Definitely.

199
00:08:07,702 --> 00:08:09,026
Gee, thanks.

200
00:08:09,061 --> 00:08:10,351
Well, so are we.

201
00:08:10,386 --> 00:08:11,782
So are we.

202
00:08:11,817 --> 00:08:13,950
We couldn't let you just run off.

203
00:08:13,985 --> 00:08:15,150
Thanks.

204
00:08:17,184 --> 00:08:18,949
John, what is up, huh?

205
00:08:18,984 --> 00:08:20,484
<i>Are you on America's most wanted?</i>

206
00:08:20,519 --> 00:08:21,649
We won't turn you in.

207
00:08:21,684 --> 00:08:23,050
Yeah, come on, out with it.

208
00:08:23,085 --> 00:08:24,050
You're among friends.

209
00:08:24,085 --> 00:08:25,317
Snoopy friends.

210
00:08:25,352 --> 00:08:26,349
Forget it.

211
00:08:26,384 --> 00:08:28,015
You are creating the mystery here.

212
00:08:28,050 --> 00:08:30,351
Obviously, you have something
you'd like to say. Say it!

213
00:08:31,984 --> 00:08:33,618
Well, maybe I...

214
00:08:34,750 --> 00:08:35,984
Ten, nine, eight, seven...

215
00:08:36,019 --> 00:08:37,050
Harry, stop.

216
00:08:38,551 --> 00:08:41,416
There is something I'm
tempted to tell you, I think.

217
00:08:41,451 --> 00:08:45,050
I've never done this before,
and I wonder how it'll pan out.

218
00:08:48,217 --> 00:08:50,517
I wonder if I could ask
you a silly question.

219
00:08:50,552 --> 00:08:51,516
John, we're teachers.

220
00:08:51,551 --> 00:08:53,484
We answer silly questions all the time.

221
00:08:53,519 --> 00:08:54,583
Hey!

222
00:08:54,618 --> 00:08:58,284
What if a man from the upper Paleolithic

223
00:08:58,319 --> 00:09:00,118
survived until the present day?

224
00:09:00,153 --> 00:09:01,917
What do you mean, survived?

225
00:09:01,952 --> 00:09:03,249
Never died?

226
00:09:03,284 --> 00:09:05,351
Yes. What would he be like?

227
00:09:05,386 --> 00:09:06,882
Well, I know some guys.

228
00:09:06,917 --> 00:09:08,734
You ever been to the Ozarks?

229
00:09:08,769 --> 00:09:10,516
It's an interesting idea.

230
00:09:10,551 --> 00:09:13,050
What, are you working on
a science fiction story?

231
00:09:13,085 --> 00:09:15,317
Say I am. What would he be like?

232
00:09:15,352 --> 00:09:16,634
Pretty tired.

233
00:09:18,528 --> 00:09:20,282
Well, seriously,

234
00:09:20,317 --> 00:09:22,484
As Art's book title suggests,

235
00:09:22,519 --> 00:09:24,651
he might be like any of us.

236
00:09:24,686 --> 00:09:25,949
Dan. A caveman?

237
00:09:25,984 --> 00:09:27,801
Well, there's no anatomical difference

238
00:09:27,836 --> 00:09:29,583
between, say, a Cro-Magnon and us.

239
00:09:29,618 --> 00:09:32,017
Except that as a rule,
we've grown taller.

240
00:09:32,052 --> 00:09:34,382
What's the selective
advantage of height?

241
00:09:34,417 --> 00:09:37,150
Better to see predators
in tall grass, my dear.

242
00:09:37,185 --> 00:09:39,449
Actually, tall and skinny

243
00:09:39,484 --> 00:09:42,351
radiates heat more
effectively in warmer climates.

244
00:09:42,386 --> 00:09:43,649
And as for neanderthals,

245
00:09:43,684 --> 00:09:45,384
I mean, we've all seen apish people.

246
00:09:45,419 --> 00:09:46,618
That strain's still with us.

247
00:09:46,653 --> 00:09:48,750
But he'd be a caveman.

248
00:09:48,785 --> 00:09:49,782
No, he wouldn't.

249
00:09:49,817 --> 00:09:50,815
John's hypothetical man

250
00:09:50,850 --> 00:09:52,618
would have lived
through 140 centuries...

251
00:09:52,653 --> 00:09:54,015
Yeah, roughly.

252
00:09:54,050 --> 00:09:56,433
...and changed with every one of them.

253
00:09:56,468 --> 00:09:58,782
I mean, assuming normal intelligence.

254
00:09:58,817 --> 00:10:01,284
Well, we think men of
the upper Paleolithic

255
00:10:01,319 --> 00:10:03,151
were as intelligent as we are.

256
00:10:03,186 --> 00:10:04,949
They just didn't know as much.

257
00:10:04,984 --> 00:10:07,950
John's man would have
learned as the race learned.

258
00:10:07,985 --> 00:10:11,118
In fact, if he had an inquiring mind,

259
00:10:11,153 --> 00:10:14,216
his knowledge might be astonishing.

260
00:10:14,251 --> 00:10:16,517
If you do write that,
let me have a look at it.

261
00:10:16,552 --> 00:10:18,783
I'm sure you'll make some
anthropological boners.

262
00:10:18,818 --> 00:10:19,882
It's a deal.

263
00:10:19,917 --> 00:10:21,767
What would keep him alive?

264
00:10:21,802 --> 00:10:23,618
What does the biologist say?

265
00:10:23,653 --> 00:10:25,282
Cigarettes.

266
00:10:25,317 --> 00:10:27,115
And ice cream.

267
00:10:27,150 --> 00:10:29,249
All right, all right, I'll play.

268
00:10:29,284 --> 00:10:32,984
All right, um, in science fiction terms,

269
00:10:33,019 --> 00:10:34,651
I would say...

270
00:10:36,184 --> 00:10:39,984
Perfect regeneration
of the body's cells,

271
00:10:40,019 --> 00:10:42,115
especially in the vital organs.

