I've got boxes to move.

543
00:21:12,783 --> 00:21:14,517
I'll give you a hand.

544
00:21:15,718 --> 00:21:20,517
Wouldn't you have
some relic, an artifact

545
00:21:20,552 --> 00:21:22,950
to remind you of your early life?

546
00:21:22,985 --> 00:21:24,451
Like this, maybe?

547
00:21:24,486 --> 00:21:25,850
Thrift shop.

548
00:21:25,885 --> 00:21:26,950
Really.

549
00:21:29,251 --> 00:21:31,618
If you lived 100... 1,000 years...

550
00:21:34,184 --> 00:21:35,616
Would you still have this?

551
00:21:35,651 --> 00:21:37,617
What would cause you to keep it?

552
00:21:37,652 --> 00:21:39,584
As a memento to your beginnings,

553
00:21:39,619 --> 00:21:41,118
even if you didn't have

554
00:21:41,153 --> 00:21:43,185
the concept of beginnings?

555
00:21:43,220 --> 00:21:45,217
It would be gone, lost.

556
00:21:46,351 --> 00:21:47,416
No.

557
00:21:47,451 --> 00:21:49,251
I don't have artifacts.

558
00:21:51,718 --> 00:21:53,117
Keep that.

559
00:21:55,251 --> 00:21:56,484
Interesting.

560
00:21:58,117 --> 00:22:00,250
You could have lied about that.

561
00:22:00,285 --> 00:22:02,384
Don't talk about me while I'm gone.

562
00:22:10,417 --> 00:22:12,216
Is he serious?

563
00:22:12,251 --> 00:22:15,015
If he is, I'm sorry to say he's...

564
00:22:15,050 --> 00:22:17,950
Oh, how could he have
concealed that for ten years?

565
00:22:17,985 --> 00:22:20,084
Least he doesn't appear to be dangerous.

566
00:22:22,783 --> 00:22:23,949
What are you doing?

567
00:22:23,984 --> 00:22:25,984
Checkin' for a hidden mic.

568
00:22:26,019 --> 00:22:27,351
<i>Candid camera.</i>

569
00:22:29,184 --> 00:22:31,134
He's fabricating these wild stories.

570
00:22:31,169 --> 00:22:33,084
I've never seen him acting like this.

571
00:22:33,119 --> 00:22:35,216
Oh, it's crazy.

572
00:22:35,251 --> 00:22:38,684
All right, all right,
as soon as you can, then.

573
00:22:45,251 --> 00:22:46,917
I love you, you know.

574
00:22:48,251 --> 00:22:49,718
I know.

575
00:22:51,517 --> 00:22:54,251
Since my first week at the office.

576
00:22:58,317 --> 00:22:59,282
And?

577
00:22:59,317 --> 00:23:02,649
I care very much about you,

578
00:23:02,684 --> 00:23:05,251
but now you know what
you'd be getting into.

579
00:23:05,286 --> 00:23:07,184
Do you really think you're a caveman?

580
00:23:07,219 --> 00:23:08,783
Do you?

581
00:23:14,817 --> 00:23:16,049
Could you love me,

582
00:23:16,084 --> 00:23:18,484
or don't you believe in that anymore?

583
00:23:19,917 --> 00:23:22,150
I've gotten over it too many times.

584
00:23:23,718 --> 00:23:25,184
Fond of you...

585
00:23:26,517 --> 00:23:28,883
certainly attracted to you.

586
00:23:31,251 --> 00:23:32,217
That's it?

587
00:23:36,317 --> 00:23:37,750
I can work with that.

588
00:23:40,950 --> 00:23:43,500
If what I'm saying is true,

589
00:23:43,535 --> 00:23:46,050
you and any children will age.

590
00:23:46,085 --> 00:23:47,349
I won't.

591
00:23:47,384 --> 00:23:49,316
And one day I'll leave.

592
00:23:49,351 --> 00:23:52,317
You'll go back to your
May-December romances.

593
00:23:52,352 --> 00:23:53,482
The simple fact is

594
00:23:53,517 --> 00:23:55,517
that I can't give you forever.

595
00:23:57,517 --> 00:23:58,917
How long's forever?

596
00:24:00,950 --> 00:24:02,850
Who ever really has it?

597
00:24:06,484 --> 00:24:09,434
My parents split up before I was born,

598
00:24:09,469 --> 00:24:12,384
And then my mom's next marriage lasted

599
00:24:12,419 --> 00:24:13,850
what, a whole three years?

600
00:24:15,850 --> 00:24:18,783
Then there's death,
illness, acts of god...

601
00:24:20,917 --> 00:24:22,950
No one knows how long they have.

602
00:24:24,718 --> 00:24:26,384
Or how little.

603
00:24:29,883 --> 00:24:31,184
I love you.

604
00:24:33,117 --> 00:24:34,718
Take whatever you can get.

605
00:24:37,750 --> 00:24:39,284
Like ten years?

606
00:24:45,317 --> 00:24:46,733
Ah! Ha ha ha!

607
00:24:48,185 --> 00:24:49,167
Uhn!

608
00:24:49,202 --> 00:24:50,115
Oh.

609
00:24:50,150 --> 00:24:52,182
Why did you do that?

610
00:24:52,217 --> 00:24:54,850
I wanted to see how fast you
were. Check your reflexes.

611
00:24:54,885 --> 00:24:57,017
I don't have eyes in
the back of my head,

612
00:24:57,052 --> 00:24:58,818
I can't hear a flea walking,

613
00:24:58,853 --> 00:25:00,549
I am not in any way superman.

614
00:25:00,584 --> 00:25:03,017
Well, I'm a second-degree black belt.

615
00:25:03,052 --> 00:25:04,850
Give it another thousand years.

616
00:25:06,484 --> 00:25:08,517
Well. I got it, I got it, I got it.

617
00:25:10,117 --> 00:25:11,082
Jesus.

618
00:25:11,117 --> 00:25:12,984
Smooth demonstration, Harry.

619
00:25:13,019 --> 00:25:15,017
Sit on it, Dan.

620
00:25:16,217 --> 00:25:17,783
I still have questions.

621
00:25:17,818 --> 00:25:19,583
I-I do too, John.

622
00:25:19,618 --> 00:25:22,217
I mean, are we done with prehistory yet?

623
00:25:22,252 --> 00:25:25,134
Remember any of your original language?

624
00:25:25,169 --> 00:25:28,017
A little. One thing
hasn't changed much...

625
00:25:31,718 --> 00:25:33,616
Did you ever do any cave art?

626
00:25:33,651 --> 00:25:35,684
Do you know the rock art at Les Eyzies?

627
00:25:35,719 --> 00:25:36,848
Mm-Hmm.

628
00:25:36,883 --> 00:25:39,217
It was the work of a man named...

629
00:25:40,783 --> 00:25:41,815
Giraud.

630
00:25:41,850 --> 00:25:43,500
He did a pretty good job.

631
00:25:43,535 --> 00:25:45,976
He would draw the animals

632
00:25:46,011 --> 00:25:48,331
that we hoped to find to eat.

633
00:25:48,366 --> 00:25:50,441
One day after a fruitless hunt,

634
00:25:50,476 --> 00:25:52,597
our chief stomped his teeth out

635
00:25:52,632 --> 00:25:54,683
because his magic had failed him.

636
00:25:54,718 --> 00:25:57,783
After that, someone had
to chew his food for him.

637
00:25:57,818 --> 00:25:59,618
Finally, he got- I suspect-

638
00:25:59,653 --> 00:26:01,715
an infected jaw,

639
00:26:01,750 --> 00:26:03,417
and he was abandoned.

640
00:26:03,452 --> 00:26:05,216
That's awful.

641
00:26:05,251 --> 00:26:07,067
You have to know what to kill.

642
00:26:07,102 --> 00:26:08,848
Is this why all your students

643
00:26:08,883 --> 00:26:11,217
say your knowledge of history is...

644
00:26:11,252 --> 00:26:12,282
so amazing?

645
00:26:12,317 --> 00:26:14,382
No, that's mostly based on study.

646
00:26:14,417 --> 00:26:18,684
Remember, it's one man,
one place at a time,

647
00:26:18,719 --> 00:26:20,982
My solitary viewpoint

648
00:26:21,017 --> 00:26:23,718
of a world I knew almost nothing about.

649
00:26:23,753 --> 00:26:24,949
Well, let's talk about

650
00:26:24,984 --> 00:26:27,017
what you say you do know about:

651
00:26:27,052 --> 00:26:28,467
Historical times.

652
00:26:28,502 --> 00:26:29,883
Don't encourage him.

653
00:26:29,918 --> 00:26:31,082
Edith.

654
00:26:31,117 --> 00:26:33,950
Next few thousand years, it got warmer.

655
00:26:33,985 --> 00:26:35,349
A few thousand years-

656
00:26:35,384 --> 00:26:37,884
See, now I know you're guessing.

657
00:26:37,919 --> 00:26:40,384
You can't get there from here, Art.

658
00:26:40,419 --> 00:26:42,750
Well then, pray, continue.

659
00:26:43,883 --> 00:26:45,750
We hunted reindeer, mammoths,

660
00:26:45,785 --> 00:26:47,748
bison, horses,

661
00:26:47,783 --> 00:26:49,284
The game retreated northward

662
00:26:49,319 --> 00:26:50,482
as the climate changed.

663
00:26:50,517 --> 00:26:52,618
You got the idea of growing food

664
00:26:52,653 --> 00:26:54,416
rather than gathering it,

665
00:26:54,451 --> 00:26:56,584
raising animals rather
than hunting them.

666
00:26:56,619 --> 00:26:58,217
Am-Am I getting warm, here?

667
00:26:58,252 --> 00:26:59,748
I bet I am.

668
00:26:59,783 --> 00:27:02,251
Lakeside living becomes commonplace,

669
00:27:02,286 --> 00:27:03,883
- Fishing, fowling...
- Come on!

670
00:27:04,984 --> 00:27:07,150
John, this is out of any textbook.

671
00:27:07,185 --> 00:27:08,182
Even yours.

672
00:27:08,217 --> 00:27:11,049
You got most of it right.

673
00:27:11,084 --> 00:27:13,100
Eventually I headed to the east.

674
00:27:13,135 --> 00:27:15,309
I'd grown curious about the world.

675
00:27:15,344 --> 00:27:17,914
I'd gotten the hang of going it alone,

676
00:27:17,949 --> 00:27:20,484
Learning how to fit in when I wanted to.

677
00:27:20,519 --> 00:27:22,349
East.

678
00:27:22,384 --> 00:27:24,249
Towards the rising sun?

679
00:27:24,284 --> 00:27:27,050
Yes. I thought it might be warmer there.

680
00:27:28,317 --> 00:27:31,184
That's when I saw an ocean.

681
00:27:32,718 --> 00:27:35,182
The Mediterranean, probably.

682
00:27:35,217 --> 00:27:37,550
It was around the
beginning of the bronze age,

683
00:27:37,585 --> 00:27:39,883
So I followed the trade
routes from the east,

684
00:27:39,918 --> 00:27:41,115
Copper, tin,

685
00:27:41,150 --> 00:27:44,283
Learning languages as I went.

686
00:27:44,318 --> 00:27:47,382
Everywhere, creation myths,

687
00:27:47,417 --> 00:27:50,150
new gods, so many, so different.

688
00:27:50,185 --> 00:27:52,883
I finally realized that it was...

689
00:27:52,918 --> 00:27:55,449
probably all hogwash,

690
00:27:55,484 --> 00:27:58,049
So I was Sumerian for 2,000 years,

691
00:27:58,084 --> 00:28:00,384
Then finally Babylonian under Hammurabi.

692
00:28:00,419 --> 00:28:01,915
Great man.

693
00:28:01,950 --> 00:28:04,482
And I sailed as a Phoenician for a time.

694
00:28:04,517 --> 00:28:07,718
See, moving on had been
easier as a hunter-gatherer...

695
00:28:09,351 --> 00:28:11,782
Difficult when villages emerged,

696
00:28:11,817 --> 00:28:15,251
tougher still in city states
where authority was centralized.

697
00:28:15,286 --> 00:28:17,049
Strangers were suspect.

698
00:28:17,084 --> 00:28:20,750
It seemed as though I
was always moving on.

699
00:28:20,785 --> 00:28:22,748
I learned some new tricks-

700
00:28:22,783 --> 00:28:25,384
even faked my death a couple of times.

701
00:28:27,584 --> 00:28:29,718
I continued east

702
00:28:29,753 --> 00:28:31,516
to India,

703
00:28:31,551 --> 00:28:35,017
luckily at the time of the Buddha.

704
00:28:35,052 --> 00:28:36,217
Luckily.

705
00:28:38,950 --> 00:28:41,684
Most extraordinary man I've ever known.

706
00:28:41,719 --> 00:28:42,848
He taught me things

707
00:28:42,883 --> 00:28:45,200
I'd never thought about before.

708
00:28:45,235 --> 00:28:47,517
You studied... with the Buddha?

709
00:28:47,552 --> 00:28:48,984
Until he died.

710
00:28:50,284 --> 00:28:53,251
He knew there was something
different about me.

711
00:28:53,286 --> 00:28:55,701
I never told him.

712
00:28:55,736 --> 00:28:58,082
This is fascinating.

713
00:28:58,117 --> 00:29:00,382
I almost wish it were true.

714
00:29:00,417 --> 00:29:04,150
Yeah, if it was true,
why are you telling us?

715
00:29:04,185 --> 00:29:05,883
I mean, we might leave here today,

716
00:29:05,918 --> 00:29:07,451
Go out there, tell everybody.

717
00:29:07,486 --> 00:29:08,984
It would vanish in disbelief.

718
00:29:10,217 --> 00:29:12,651
A story that goes around the room.

719
00:29:12,686 --> 00:29:14,715
No credibility.

720
00:29:14,750 --> 00:29:17,850
Even if I could make you believe me,

721
00:29:17,885 --> 00:29:19,583
in a month, you wouldn't.

722
00:29:19,618 --> 00:29:22,118
Some of you would call me a psychopath,

723
00:29:22,153 --> 00:29:24,618
Others would be angry
at a pointless joke.

724
00:29:24,653 --> 00:29:26,652
Some of us are angry now.

725
00:29:26,687 --> 00:29:28,616
This-this was a bad idea.

726
00:29:28,651 --> 00:29:31,384
Uh, I love you all, and I do not want

727
00:29:31,419 --> 00:29:32,751
to put you through anything.

728
00:29:32,786 --> 00:29:34,049
Then why are you doing it?

729
00:29:34,084 --> 00:29:36,384
'Cause I wanted
to say good-bye-

730
00:29:36,419 --> 00:29:37,349
As yourself.

731
00:29:37,384 --> 00:29:38,917
I think you've done that,

732
00:29:38,952 --> 00:29:40,017
whoever that self is.

733
00:29:40,052 --> 00:29:41,249
Easy, Edith.

734
00:29:41,284 --> 00:29:42,915
We're just grading his homework.

735
00:29:42,950 --> 00:29:45,750
I see what's going on. You're
playing the good cop, Dan.

736
00:29:45,785 --> 00:29:47,082
That's fine. Just enjoy it.

737
00:29:47,117 --> 00:29:49,783
All right, I think this
whole thing is just a crock!

738
00:29:49,818 --> 00:29:51,516
I should leave, but I'm gonna stay.

739
00:29:51,551 --> 00:29:54,251
You know why? 'Cause I wanna
see what this is all about.

740
00:29:54,286 --> 00:29:55,782
So do I. What is this all about?

741
00:29:55,817 --> 00:29:57,917
Let's ask Dr. Freud,
who's just arrived.

742
00:29:57,952 --> 00:29:59,317
Hey, Will! Will!

743
00:30:01,317 --> 00:30:02,251
Art. Hey.

744
00:30:03,551 --> 00:30:04,616
John!

745
00:30:04,651 --> 00:30:06,115
I'm glad I caught you.

746
00:30:06,150 --> 00:30:08,083
Someone mentioned
that you were leaving-

747
00:30:08,118 --> 00:30:09,982
Called you, told you that I've lost it.

748
00:30:10,017 --> 00:30:12,783
Glad you're here. Things are
going in unexpected directions.

749
00:30:12,818 --> 00:30:14,050
Yes, so I hear.

750
00:30:14,085 --> 00:30:15,316
Hi.

751
00:30:15,351 --> 00:30:16,934
Are you hungry?

752
00:30:16,969 --> 00:30:18,482
Uh, thank you, no.

753
00:30:18,517 --> 00:30:20,684
Whiskey? Johnny Walker green.

754
00:30:20,719 --> 00:30:22,684
Oh, yes.

755
00:30:26,084 --> 00:30:28,684
You look very familiar,
my dear. Linda Murphy.

756
00:30:28,719 --> 00:30:31,284
I'm in your tuesday
psych 1 class, Dr. Gruber.

757
00:30:31,319 --> 00:30:33,850
Ah, well, this lesson may be something

758
00:30:33,885 --> 00:30:36,915
I could not have imagined.

759
00:30:36,950 --> 00:30:41,282
I regret being so
obvious about this, John,

760
00:30:41,317 --> 00:30:44,584
but these people are all
very concerned for you.

761
00:30:44,619 --> 00:30:47,216
Yes, I'm cutting out paper dinosaurs.

762
00:30:47,251 --> 00:30:50,417
I really wish I'd been
here from the beginning.

763
00:30:50,452 --> 00:30:51,449
Me too.

764
00:30:51,484 --> 00:30:53,482
Let me just say something right now.

765
00:30:53,517 --> 00:30:55,850
There's absolutely no
way in the whole world

766
00:30:55,885 --> 00:30:58,616
for John to prove this story to us,

767
00:30:58,651 --> 00:31:01,618
just like there's no way
for us to disprove it.

768
00:31:01,653 --> 00:31:03,815
No matter how outrageous we think it is,

769
00:31:03,850 --> 00:31:07,117
no matter how highly trained
some of us think we are,

770
00:31:07,152 --> 00:31:09,316
there's absolutely
no way to disprove it.

771
00:31:09,351 --> 00:31:13,817
Our friend is either a
caveman, a liar, or a nut.

772
00:31:13,852 --> 00:31:15,317
So while we're thinking about that,

773
00:31:15,352 --> 00:31:17,984
why don't we just go with it?

774
00:31:18,019 --> 00:31:19,449
I mean, hell, who knows,

775
00:31:19,484 --> 00:31:21,500
he might jolt us into believing him,

776
00:31:21,535 --> 00:31:23,517
or we might jolt him back to reality.

777
00:31:23,552 --> 00:31:26,034
Believing? Whose reality?

778
00:31:26,069 --> 00:31:28,517
So... you're a caveman.

779
00:31:28,552 --> 00:31:29,815
Yes. Uh...

780
00:31:29,850 --> 00:31:33,282
<i>Uh, I was a Cro-Magnon, I think.</i>

781
00:31:33,317 --> 00:31:36,084
You don't know if
you're a caveman or not?

782
00:31:36,119 --> 00:31:37,384
No, I'm sure about that.

783
00:31:37,419 --> 00:31:38,516
A Cro-Magnon, then.

784
00:31:38,551 --> 00:31:40,649
When did you first realize this?

785
00:31:40,684 --> 00:31:42,883
When the Cro-Magnon
was first identified,

786
00:31:42,918 --> 00:31:44,984
when anthropology gave them a name,

787
00:31:45,019 --> 00:31:46,482
I had mine.

788
00:31:46,517 --> 00:31:47,915
Well, please continue.

789
00:31:47,950 --> 00:31:49,883
I'm sure you must have more to say.

790
00:31:49,918 --> 00:31:51,817
Would you like me to lie on the couch?

791
00:31:51,852 --> 00:31:54,417
As you wish.

792
00:31:56,284 --> 00:31:58,882
As a physician, I'm curious.

793
00:31:58,917 --> 00:32:02,251
In this enormous lifetime you describe,

794
00:32:02,286 --> 00:32:04,101
have you ever been ill?

795
00:32:04,136 --> 00:32:05,917
Sure, as much as anyone.

796
00:32:05,952 --> 00:32:07,484
Seriously ill?

797
00:32:07,519 --> 00:32:08,982
Sometimes.

798
00:32:09,017 --> 00:32:10,949
Of what? Do you know?

799
00:32:10,984 --> 00:32:12,550
In prehistory, I can't tell you.

800
00:32:12,585 --> 00:32:14,117
Maybe pneumonia once or twice.

801
00:32:16,150 --> 00:32:18,015
Last few hundred years,

802
00:32:18,050 --> 00:32:21,217
I've gotten over typhoid, yellow fever,

803
00:32:21,252 --> 00:32:24,384
smallpox... I survived the black plague.

804
00:32:24,419 --> 00:32:25,683
Bubonic?

805
00:32:25,718 --> 00:32:27,082
Oh, that's terrible.

806
00:32:27,117 --> 00:32:28,815
More so than history describes.

807
00:32:28,850 --> 00:32:32,384
And smallpox.
- But you're not scarred.

808
00:32:32,419 --> 00:32:33,583
I don't scar.

809
00:32:33,618 --> 00:32:34,984
No, John, that is not possible.

810
00:32:35,019 --> 00:32:36,316
Please, let's take John's story

811
00:32:36,351 --> 00:32:39,467
at face value and explore
it from that perspective.

812
00:32:39,502 --> 00:32:42,584
If he doesn't scar, it's
no stranger than the rest.

813
00:32:42,619 --> 00:32:45,050
John, would you please stop by my lab,

814
00:32:45,085 --> 00:32:46,882
suffer a few tests from

815
00:32:46,917 --> 00:32:48,750
your friendly neighborhood biologist.

816
00:32:48,785 --> 00:32:50,082
I'm leery of labs.

817
00:32:50,117 --> 00:32:52,433
Afraid I might go in and
stay for a thousand years

818
00:32:52,468 --> 00:32:54,750
while cigarette smoking
men try to figure me out.

819
00:32:54,785 --> 00:32:56,618
You don't think that I would betray you?

820
00:32:56,653 --> 00:32:58,082
Walls have ears.

821
00:32:58,117 --> 00:33:00,618
Medical tests might be a
way of proving what you say.

822
00:33:00,653 --> 00:33:01,835
I don't wanna prove it.

823
00:33:01,870 --> 00:33:03,010
So you're telling us this,

824
00:33:03,045 --> 00:33:04,115
the yarn of the century,

825
00:33:04,150 --> 00:33:05,884
And you don't care if
we believe it or not?

826
00:33:05,919 --> 00:33:07,585
I guess I shouldn't
have expected you to.

827
00:33:07,620 --> 00:33:09,251
You're not as crazy as you think I am.

828
00:33:09,286 --> 00:33:10,216
Amen.

829
00:33:10,251 --> 00:33:11,717
I've always liked you.

830
00:33:11,752 --> 00:33:13,168
Why, thank you, dear.

831
00:33:13,203 --> 00:33:14,549
Now that's changing.

832
00:33:14,584 --> 00:33:16,082
Surely you don't believe this nonsense.

833
00:33:16,117 --> 00:33:18,150
I think we should remain
courteous to someone

834
00:33:18,185 --> 00:33:19,782
who we've known and trusted, Edith.

835
00:33:19,817 --> 00:33:22,517
Here you sit.
You can't break his story.

836
00:33:22,552 --> 00:33:25,217
All you can do is thumb your nose at it.

837
00:33:25,252 --> 00:33:27,251
Is that what you're doing, John?

838
00:33:27,286 --> 00:33:28,935
Are you laughing at us inside?

839
00:33:28,970 --> 00:33:30,549
I wish you didn't feel that way.

840
00:33:30,584 --> 00:33:33,950
What you're saying -
it offends common sense.

841
00:33:33,985 --> 00:33:35,783
So does relativity, quantum mechanics-

842
00:33:35,818 --> 00:33:37,449
That's the way nature works.

843
00:33:37,484 --> 00:33:41,883
But your story doesn't fit
into nature as we know it.

844
00:33:41,918 --> 00:33:43,618
But we know so little, Dan.

845
00:33:44,684 --> 00:33:45,917
We know so little.

846
00:33:45,952 --> 00:33:47,115
How many of you know

847
00:33:47,150 --> 00:33:48,434
five geniuses in your field

848
00:33:48,469 --> 00:33:49,683
that you disagree with...

849
00:33:49,718 --> 00:33:51,317
One you would like to strangle?

850
00:33:51,352 --> 00:33:53,482
Strangle them all.

851
00:33:53,517 --> 00:33:55,150
It's bad enough we have to listen

852
00:33:55,185 --> 00:33:56,418
to Harry's idiotic jokes.

853
00:33:56,453 --> 00:33:57,616
Thank you very much, Edith.

854
00:33:57,651 --> 00:34:00,050
Maybe when I'm 110, I'll
be as smart as you are.

855
00:34:00,085 --> 00:34:01,517
If you lived as long as John did,

856
00:34:01,552 --> 00:34:03,201
you still wouldn't grow up.

857
00:34:03,236 --> 00:34:04,815
Come on, guys. Take it easy.

858
00:34:04,850 --> 00:34:07,317
How often do we get to meet someone

859
00:34:07,352 --> 00:34:10,783
who says he's a stone age man?

860
00:34:10,818 --> 00:34:12,050
Well, once is enough.

861
00:34:12,085 --> 00:34:13,449
Edith.

862
00:34:13,484 --> 00:34:15,584
All right. A guy with your mind-

863
00:34:15,619 --> 00:34:17,649
you'd have studied a great deal.

864
00:34:17,684 --> 00:34:21,117
I have ten degrees,
including all of yours...

865
00:34:21,152 --> 00:34:23,516
Except yours, Will.

866
00:34:23,551 --> 00:34:25,718
That makes me feel a trifle lilliputian.

867
00:34:25,753 --> 00:34:28,082
That's over the span of 170 years.

868
00:34:28,117 --> 00:34:31,351
I got my biology degree
at Oxford in 1840,

869
00:34:31,386 --> 00:34:33,084
So I'm a little behind the times.

870
00:34:33,119 --> 00:34:34,382
The same in other areas-

871
00:34:34,417 --> 00:34:37,184
I can't keep up with the
new stuff that comes along.

872
00:34:37,219 --> 00:34:38,149
No one can.

873
00:34:38,184 --> 00:34:39,484
Not even in their specialty.

874
00:34:39,519 --> 00:34:41,049
So much for the myth

875
00:34:41,084 --> 00:34:42,817
of the super-wise,
all-knowing immortal.

876
00:34:42,852 --> 00:34:44,715
I see your point, John.

877
00:34:44,750 --> 00:34:46,382
No matter how long a man lives,

878
00:34:46,417 --> 00:34:48,516
he can't be in advance of his times.

879
00:34:48,551 --> 00:34:51,551
He can't know more than
the best of the race knows,

880
00:34:51,586 --> 00:34:54,551
if that- I mean, when the
world learned it was round,

881
00:34:54,586 --> 00:34:55,901
you learned it.

882
00:34:55,936 --> 00:34:57,260
It took some time.

883
00:34:57,295 --> 00:34:58,549
News traveled slowly

884
00:34:58,584 --> 00:35:00,484
before communications were fancy.

885
00:35:00,519 --> 00:35:03,115
There were social obstacles,

886
00:35:03,150 --> 00:35:06,351
preconceptions, screams from the church.

887
00:35:06,386 --> 00:35:07,516
Ten doctorates.

888
00:35:07,551 --> 00:35:09,417
That's impressive,
John. Did you teach them?

889
00:35:09,452 --> 00:35:10,782
Some.

890
00:35:10,817 --> 00:35:13,416
You might have all done the same.

891
00:35:13,451 --> 00:35:16,584
Living 14,000 years
didn't make me a genius.

892
00:35:16,619 --> 00:35:17,917
I just had time.

893
00:35:17,952 --> 00:35:19,549
Time.

894
00:35:19,584 --> 00:35:21,549
We can't see it, we can't hear it,

895
00:35:21,584 --> 00:35:25,284
we can't weigh it, we can't
measure it in a laboratory.

896
00:35:25,319 --> 00:35:27,549
It's a subjective sense of becoming

897
00:35:27,584 --> 00:35:32,050
what we are instead of what
we were a nanosecond ago,

898
00:35:32,085 --> 00:35:34,484
becoming what we will
be in another nanosecond.

899
00:35:34,519 --> 00:35:36,518
The Hopis see time as a landscape,

900
00:35:36,553 --> 00:35:39,002
existing before and behind us,

901
00:35:39,037 --> 00:35:41,451
and we move--
we move through it,

902
00:35:41,486 --> 00:35:43,249
slice by slice.

903
00:35:43,284 --> 00:35:44,549
Clocks measure time.

904
00:35:44,584 --> 00:35:45,949
No, they measure themselves.

905
00:35:45,984 --> 00:35:48,349
The objective referent
of clock is another clock.

906
00:35:48,384 --> 00:35:50,783
How very interesting. What
has it got to do with John?

907
00:35:50,818 --> 00:35:52,815
Oh, he- he might be a man

908
00:35:52,850 --> 00:35:57,883
who lives outside of time as we know it.

909
00:36:00,384 --> 00:36:02,882
Yes, uh, well.

910
00:36:02,917 --> 00:36:06,033
People do go around armed these days.

911
00:36:06,068 --> 00:36:09,150
If I shot you, John...
You're immortal?

912
00:36:09,185 --> 00:36:11,115
Would you survive this?

913
00:36:11,150 --> 00:36:13,917
I never said I was immortal, just old.

914
00:36:13,952 --> 00:36:15,115
I might die.

915
00:36:15,150 --> 00:36:16,549
And then you could wonder

916
00:36:16,584 --> 00:36:18,950
the rest of your incarcerated
life what you shot.

917
00:36:20,651 --> 00:36:23,417
Well, uh, may I?

918
00:36:25,084 --> 00:36:26,748
Preferable to a gun.

919
00:36:26,783 --> 00:36:30,050
Will, that was a bit much.

920
00:36:30,085 --> 00:36:32,701
Ooh. Books.

921
00:36:32,736 --> 00:36:35,282
Doctorates.

922
00:36:35,317 --> 00:36:38,533
Yes, you have grown and changed.

923
00:36:38,568 --> 00:36:40,959
But there is always innate nature.

924
00:36:40,994 --> 00:36:43,351
Wouldn't you be more comfortable

925
00:36:43,386 --> 00:36:44,984
squatting in the backyard?

926
00:36:45,019 --> 00:36:46,501
Sometimes I do, Will.

927
00:36:46,536 --> 00:36:47,984
Look up at the stars.

928
00:36:48,019 --> 00:36:49,015
Wonder.

929
00:36:49,050 --> 00:36:51,451
And what did primitive man make of them?

930
00:36:51,486 --> 00:36:53,382
A great mystery.

931
00:36:53,417 --> 00:36:55,815
There were gods up there then.

932
00:36:55,850 --> 00:36:58,351
Shamans who knew about them told us.

933
00:36:58,386 --> 00:36:59,618
They still do.

934
00:37:01,184 --> 00:37:03,084
Have you ever wished it would end?

935
00:37:05,718 --> 00:37:06,683
No.

936
00:37:06,718 --> 00:37:09,082
Fourteen thousand years.

937
00:37:09,117 --> 00:37:11,767
Injuries, illness, disasters.

938
00:37:11,802 --> 00:37:14,126
You've survived them all.

939
00:37:14,161 --> 00:37:16,451
You're a very lucky man.

940
00:37:21,769 --> 00:37:22,984
Come in.

941
00:37:25,950 --> 00:37:27,050
John Oldman?

942
00:37:27,085 --> 00:37:28,416
Yes.

943
00:37:28,451 --> 00:37:30,351
Charity now. We're here
to pick up the furniture.

944
00:37:30,386 --> 00:37:32,149
It's all yours.

945
00:37:32,184 --> 00:37:33,416
Here, take this chair.

946
00:37:33,451 --> 00:37:35,417
I'm gonna go drink in the corner.

947
00:37:37,384 --> 00:37:39,984
You're, uh... you're donating it?

948
00:37:40,019 --> 00:37:41,218
Everything?

949
00:37:41,253 --> 00:37:42,382
I'll get more.

950
00:37:42,417 --> 00:37:43,950
Do you always travel this light?

951
00:37:43,985 --> 00:37:46,084
It's the only way to move.

952
00:37:47,783 --> 00:37:49,649
Oh, you-

953
00:37:49,684 --> 00:37:51,216
You've talked a good deal

954
00:37:51,251 --> 00:37:54,484
about your extraordinary
amount of living.

955
00:37:54,519 --> 00:37:56,684
What do you think of dying, John?

956
00:37:56,719 --> 00:37:58,317
Do you fear death?

957
00:37:58,352 --> 00:37:59,616
Who wouldn't?

958
00:37:59,651 --> 00:38:01,784
How did primitive man regard death?

959
00:38:01,819 --> 00:38:03,917
Well, we had the practical concept.

960
00:38:03,952 --> 00:38:05,884
You know, we stopped,

961
00:38:05,919 --> 00:38:07,782
fell down, didn't get up,

962
00:38:07,817 --> 00:38:10,017
Started to smell bad, come apart.

963
00:38:10,052 --> 00:38:12,182
Injuries we could understand.

964
00:38:12,217 --> 00:38:14,783
If someone's insides
were all over the ground.

965
00:38:14,818 --> 00:38:16,115
Infections...

966
00:38:16,150 --> 00:38:20,618
They were, uh, mysterious.

967
00:38:21,750 --> 00:38:23,182
Aging...

968
00:38:23,217 --> 00:38:24,748
The biggest mystery of all.

969
00:38:24,783 --> 00:38:26,782
You realized you were different.

970
00:38:26,817 --> 00:38:29,883
<i>Longer to realize how I was different,</i>

971
00:38:29,918 --> 00:38:31,715
to find a way to synthesize

972
00:38:31,750 --> 00:38:34,266
my experience into a view of myself.

973
00:38:34,301 --> 00:38:36,783
At first, I thought everybody had

974
00:38:36,818 --> 00:38:38,549
something wrong with them.

975
00:38:38,584 --> 00:38:42,184
They got old and they
died, animals, too...

976
00:38:42,219 --> 00:38:43,249
but not me.

977
00:38:46,202 --> 00:38:49,050
Oh, forgive me, my dear.

978
00:38:49,085 --> 00:38:50,715
You live simply.

979
00:38:50,750 --> 00:38:53,251
I've owned castles, but why leave a lot

980
00:38:53,286 --> 00:38:54,551
if you're always leaving?

981
00:38:54,586 --> 00:38:55,782
I have money.

982
00:38:55,817 --> 00:38:58,551
What, you get into
AT&T at 50 cents, John?

983
00:39:00,783 --> 00:39:02,482
As one grows older,

984
00:39:02,517 --> 00:39:07,850
the days, weeks, months
go by more quickly.

985
00:39:07,885 --> 00:39:10,951
What does a day or a year

986
00:39:10,986 --> 00:39:13,568
or a century mean to you?

987
00:39:13,603 --> 00:39:16,150
The birth-death cycle?

988
00:39:16,185 --> 00:39:17,801
Turbulence.

989
00:39:17,836 --> 00:39:19,382
I meet someone,

990
00:39:19,417 --> 00:39:22,251
learn their name, say
a word, they're gone.

991
00:39:22,286 --> 00:39:26,684
Others come like waves. Rise, fall.

992
00:39:28,251 --> 00:39:30,651
Ripples in a wheat
field, blown by the wind.

993
00:39:30,686 --> 00:39:33,384
Do you ever get tired of it all?

994
00:39:33,419 --> 00:39:34,815
I get bored now and then.

995
00:39:34,850 --> 00:39:38,117
They keep making the same
stupid mistakes over and over.

996
00:39:38,152 --> 00:39:39,050
They.

997
00:39:40,117 --> 00:39:41,349
Then you see yourself

998
00:39:41,384 --> 00:39:43,584
as separate from the rest of humanity.

999
00:39:44,651 --> 00:39:46,384
I didn't mean it that way.

1000
00:39:47,684 --> 00:39:48,850
But of course...

1001
00:39:50,017 --> 00:39:51,015
I am.

1002
00:39:52,417 --> 00:39:55,249
Are you comfortable
knowing that you have lived

1003
00:39:55,284 --> 00:39:59,150
while everyone you knew
- Everyone you knew, John! -

1004
00:39:59,185 --> 00:40:00,316
has died?

1005
00:40:00,351 --> 00:40:02,117
I've regretted losing people...

1006
00:40:02,152 --> 00:40:03,149
often.

1007
00:40:03,184 --> 00:40:05,584
Have you ever felt guilt about that,

1008
00:40:05,619 --> 00:40:07,868
something akin to survivor's guilt?

1009
00:40:07,903 --> 00:40:10,117
In the strict psychological sense?

1010
00:40:10,152 --> 00:40:11,484
I suppose I have.

1011
00:40:11,519 --> 00:40:12,618
Yeah.

1012
00:40:14,084 --> 00:40:16,184
But what can I do about it?

1013
00:40:18,184 --> 00:40:19,684
Indeed.

1014
00:40:20,783 --> 00:40:22,017
I'm sorry, ma'am.

1015
00:40:22,052 --> 00:40:23,216
Gentlemen, I'm-

1016
00:40:23,251 --> 00:40:25,184
I'm gonna keep the couch.

1017
00:40:25,219 --> 00:40:26,149
Thanks.

1018
00:40:26,184 --> 00:40:28,349
Ladies? Will? Oh, no...

1019
00:40:28,384 --> 00:40:31,017
You've got a heart condition.
Don't grump about it.

1020
00:40:31,052 --> 00:40:32,817
Hey, how about changing
the subject, Will?

1021
00:40:32,852 --> 00:40:34,616
Enough with the- with the dying.

1022
00:40:34,651 --> 00:40:38,351
But this is the flip
side of his coin, Harry.

1023
00:40:38,386 --> 00:40:41,149
I'm very curious to know his feelings.

1024
00:40:41,184 --> 00:40:44,084
Would you prefer I asked
him about his father?

1025
00:40:44,119 --> 00:40:45,517
I thought you always started with

1026
00:40:45,552 --> 00:40:46,882
"Tell me about your mother."

1027
00:40:46,917 --> 00:40:49,950
Yes, but prehistory was
strongly patriarchal.

1028
00:40:49,985 --> 00:40:53,101
Surely you remember your father.

1029
00:40:53,136 --> 00:40:56,182
I seem to remember a figure,

1030
00:40:56,217 --> 00:40:59,150
Perhaps an older brother,
a social father, maybe.

1031
00:40:59,185 --> 00:41:00,848
Well, no matter.

1032
00:41:00,883 --> 00:41:03,251
I can scarcely remember mine.

1033
00:41:04,750 --> 00:41:07,282
Do you feel a vacancy

1034
00:41:07,317 --> 00:41:09,334
in your life about that, John,

1035
00:41:09,369 --> 00:41:11,351
something you wish could be filled

1036
00:41:11,386 --> 00:41:14,251
by a face, a voice, an image?

1037
00:41:16,651 --> 00:41:18,115
Not at this late date.

1038
00:41:18,150 --> 00:41:20,451
There must be
someone - probably many -

1039
00:41:20,486 --> 00:41:22,184
that you valued intensely.

1040
00:41:22,219 --> 00:41:23,583
Loved.

1041
00:41:23,618 --> 00:41:27,115
You saw them age and die -

1042
00:41:27,150 --> 00:41:30,583
a friend, a colleague, a wife.

1043
00:41:30,618 --> 00:41:33,917
Certainly you've had wives and children?

1044
00:41:33,952 --> 00:41:35,316
I'd move on.

1045
00:41:35,351 --> 00:41:37,149
I had to move on.

1046
00:41:37,184 --> 00:41:39,883
Making him history's biggest bigamist.

1047
00:41:40,984 --> 00:41:43,651
Have you ever in your life thought

1048
00:41:43,686 --> 00:41:45,284
"It should have been me"?

1049
00:41:47,551 --> 00:41:48,616
Maybe.

1050
00:41:48,651 --> 00:41:50,115
Yeah, Art has told me

1051
00:41:50,150 --> 00:41:51,915
that some of your early fellows

1052
00:41:51,950 --> 00:41:54,633
feared you were stealing their lives.

1053
00:41:54,668 --> 00:41:57,317
Have you thought that perhaps you were?

1054
00:41:57,352 --> 00:41:58,782
Perhaps you are!

1055
00:41:58,817 --> 00:42:02,017
There have always been
legends of such a thing,

1056
00:42:02,052 --> 00:42:04,082
a creature not quite human

1057
00:42:04,117 --> 00:42:08,184
taking not the blood,
but the life force itself?

1058
00:42:08,219 --> 00:42:09,482
My God, Will.

1059
00:42:09,517 --> 00:42:11,949
Unconsciously, perhaps,

1060
00:42:11,984 --> 00:42:15,984
by some biological or psychic mechanism

1061
00:42:16,019 --> 00:42:17,982
that we can only guess at.

1062
00:42:18,017 --> 00:42:21,017
I'm not saying you would do
such a thing deliberately.

1063
00:42:21,052 --> 00:42:24,084
I'm not saying that you
would even know how to...

1064
00:42:24,119 --> 00:42:25,417
Would you?

1065
00:42:26,950 --> 00:42:29,850
But would such a thing be fair?

1066
00:42:29,885 --> 00:42:31,516
So you believe me now?

1067
00:42:31,551 --> 00:42:34,882
I'm only exploring what you have said.

1068
00:42:34,917 --> 00:42:38,817
Whether I believe it or
not is of no importance.

1069
00:42:38,852 --> 00:42:40,634
We will die.

1070
00:42:40,669 --> 00:42:42,382
You will live.

1071
00:42:42,417 --> 00:42:44,551
Will you come to my funeral, John?

1072
00:42:44,586 --> 00:42:45,835
Hey, Will...

1073
00:42:45,870 --> 00:42:47,049
You've gone too far.

1074
00:42:47,084 --> 00:42:49,750
John didn't ask to be what he is.

1075
00:42:49,785 --> 00:42:52,417
And we did not ask to hear about it.

1076
00:42:52,452 --> 00:42:53,949
But if it were true,

1077
00:42:53,984 --> 00:42:57,050
is there one among us
who would not feel envy,

1078
00:42:57,085 --> 00:42:59,551
even perhaps a touch of hatred?

1079
00:43:01,317 --> 00:43:03,267
