commandments in ten words:

1342
00:53:50,686 --> 00:53:52,216
Don't. Don't, don't, don't,

1343
00:53:52,251 --> 00:53:54,050
Don't, don't, don't,
don't, don't, don't.

1344
00:53:54,085 --> 00:53:55,649
Don't.

1345
00:53:55,684 --> 00:53:58,750
The commandments are just modern
updates of more ancient laws.

1346
00:53:58,785 --> 00:54:00,583
Hammurabi's code.

1347
00:54:00,618 --> 00:54:03,117
That's right, they
weren't the first, right?

1348
00:54:03,152 --> 00:54:06,084
Edith, I was raised on the Torah...

1349
00:54:06,119 --> 00:54:07,549
My wife, on the Koran.

1350
00:54:07,584 --> 00:54:09,217
My oldest son is an atheist.

1351
00:54:09,252 --> 00:54:11,067
My youngest is a Scientologist.

1352
00:54:11,102 --> 00:54:12,848
My daughter is studying Hinduism.

1353
00:54:12,883 --> 00:54:17,117
I imagine that there is room there
for a holy war in my living room,

1354
00:54:17,152 --> 00:54:19,317
but we practice live and let live.

1355
00:54:20,651 --> 00:54:22,084
Why don't you sit down?

1356
00:54:29,184 --> 00:54:32,117
What is your preferred
version of the Bible?

1357
00:54:32,152 --> 00:54:33,583
The King James, of course.

1358
00:54:33,618 --> 00:54:36,084
It's the most modern, the
work of great scholars.

1359
00:54:36,119 --> 00:54:37,584
Modern is good.

1360
00:54:39,384 --> 00:54:41,618
All right, John,
hit us with the short form.

1361
00:54:43,651 --> 00:54:45,684
Guy met the Buddha, liked what he heard,

1362
00:54:45,719 --> 00:54:47,518
thought about it for a while -

1363
00:54:47,553 --> 00:54:49,317
say 500 years, while he returned

1364
00:54:49,352 --> 00:54:51,318
to the Mediterranean,

1365
00:54:51,353 --> 00:54:53,249
became an Etruscan.

1366
00:54:53,284 --> 00:54:55,001
Seeped into the Roman empire.

1367
00:54:55,036 --> 00:54:56,718
He didn't like what they became -

1368
00:54:56,753 --> 00:54:58,949
A giant killing machine.

1369
00:54:58,984 --> 00:55:00,683
He went to the Near East thinking,

1370
00:55:00,718 --> 00:55:03,984
"Why not pass the Buddha's
teachings on in a modern form."

1371
00:55:04,019 --> 00:55:06,216
So he tried.

1372
00:55:06,251 --> 00:55:08,417
One dissident against Rome?

1373
00:55:08,452 --> 00:55:09,583
Rome won.

1374
00:55:09,618 --> 00:55:10,982
The rest is history.

1375
00:55:11,017 --> 00:55:13,484
Well, sort of. Lot of
fairy tales mixed in.

1376
00:55:16,317 --> 00:55:18,282
I knew it.

1377
00:55:18,317 --> 00:55:20,250
He's saying he was Christ.

1378
00:55:20,285 --> 00:55:22,149
Oh, no. That's the medal

1379
00:55:22,184 --> 00:55:24,517
they pinned on Jesus
to fulfill prophecy.

1380
00:55:24,552 --> 00:55:25,715
The crucifixion.

1381
00:55:25,750 --> 00:55:28,750
He blocked the pain
as he had learned to do

1382
00:55:28,785 --> 00:55:30,115
in Tibet and India.

1383
00:55:30,150 --> 00:55:32,516
He also learned to
slow his body processes

1384
00:55:32,551 --> 00:55:35,150
down to the point where
they were undetectable.

1385
00:55:35,185 --> 00:55:36,584
They thought he was dead.

1386
00:55:36,619 --> 00:55:37,949
So his followers pulled him

1387
00:55:37,984 --> 00:55:40,282
from the cross, placed him in a cave...

1388
00:55:40,317 --> 00:55:42,950
His body normalized as
he had trained it to.

1389
00:55:44,217 --> 00:55:46,683
He attempted to go away undetected,

1390
00:55:46,718 --> 00:55:49,150
but some devotees were standing watch.

1391
00:55:50,584 --> 00:55:53,034
Tried to explain.

1392
00:55:53,069 --> 00:55:55,449
They were ecstatic.

1393
00:55:55,484 --> 00:55:57,949
Thus, I was resurrected,

1394
00:55:57,984 --> 00:56:00,000
and I ascended to central Europe

1395
00:56:00,035 --> 00:56:01,982
to get away as far as possible.

1396
00:56:02,017 --> 00:56:04,484
You don't mean a word of this, John.

1397
00:56:04,519 --> 00:56:06,484
My God, why are you doing this?

1398
00:56:06,519 --> 00:56:08,050
Let me see your wrists.

1399
00:56:08,085 --> 00:56:09,516
I don't scar.

1400
00:56:09,551 --> 00:56:11,182
Besides, they tied me...

1401
00:56:11,217 --> 00:56:14,384
but nails and blood make
better religious art.

1402
00:56:14,419 --> 00:56:17,551
All the speculations about Jesus.

1403
00:56:17,586 --> 00:56:19,316
He was black, he was Asian,

1404
00:56:19,351 --> 00:56:21,834
he was a blue-eyed Aryan
with a golden beard

1405
00:56:21,869 --> 00:56:24,282
and hair straight out
of Vidal Sassoon's,

1406
00:56:24,317 --> 00:56:27,484
He was a benevolent alien,
he never existed at all.

1407
00:56:27,519 --> 00:56:29,616
Now he's a caveman.

1408
00:56:29,651 --> 00:56:32,750
The Christ figure goes all
the way back to Krishna -

1409
00:56:32,785 --> 00:56:33,834
Hercules, of course.

1410
00:56:33,869 --> 00:56:34,848
Hercules?

1411
00:56:34,883 --> 00:56:37,550
Born of a virgin, Alcmene.

1412
00:56:37,585 --> 00:56:40,217
A god for a father, Zeus.

1413
00:56:40,252 --> 00:56:42,848
The only begotten.

1414
00:56:42,883 --> 00:56:45,449
<i>The savior
- The greek? Soter.</i>

1415
00:56:45,484 --> 00:56:47,616
The good shepherd, the prince of peace,

1416
00:56:47,651 --> 00:56:50,184
bringing gentle persuasion
and divine wisdom.

1417
00:56:50,219 --> 00:56:53,018
He died, joined his father on Olympus

1418
00:56:53,053 --> 00:56:55,782
a thousand years before Gethsemane.

1419
00:56:55,817 --> 00:56:59,684
How can you compare pagan
mythology to the true word?

1420
00:56:59,719 --> 00:57:02,251
Pretty damn closely, I'd say.

1421
00:57:02,286 --> 00:57:04,748
The early Christian leaders,

1422
00:57:04,783 --> 00:57:06,683
they threw away Hebrew manuscripts

1423
00:57:06,718 --> 00:57:09,618
and borrowed from pagan
sources all over the place.

1424
00:57:09,653 --> 00:57:12,249
Do you realize how...

1425
00:57:12,284 --> 00:57:14,516
inconsiderately you're
treating my feelings?

1426
00:57:14,551 --> 00:57:18,050
About as inconsiderately
as we're treating John's.

1427
00:57:18,085 --> 00:57:20,316
Well, he doesn't
believe what he's saying!

1428
00:57:20,351 --> 00:57:22,917
Do you believe literally
everything in the Bible, Edith?

1429
00:57:22,952 --> 00:57:24,049
Yes!

1430
00:57:24,084 --> 00:57:25,449
Before you say it,

1431
00:57:25,484 --> 00:57:28,150
I know it's undergone a lot of changes,

1432
00:57:28,185 --> 00:57:30,651
But God has spoken through man

1433
00:57:30,686 --> 00:57:32,683
to make his word clearer.

1434
00:57:32,718 --> 00:57:35,115
He couldn't get it right the first time?

1435
00:57:35,150 --> 00:57:38,350
We're imperfect! He had to
work to make us understand.

1436
00:57:38,385 --> 00:57:41,516
<i>He couldn't get us right
the first time, Edith?</i>

1437
00:57:41,551 --> 00:57:44,351
Taken alone, the
philosophical teachings of Jesus

1438
00:57:44,386 --> 00:57:46,482
are Buddhism with a Hebrew accent.

1439
00:57:46,517 --> 00:57:50,284
Kindness, tolerance, brotherhood, love,

1440
00:57:50,319 --> 00:57:51,982
a ruthless realism acknowledging

1441
00:57:52,017 --> 00:57:55,251
that life is as it is here
on Earth, here and now.

1442
00:57:55,286 --> 00:57:58,385
The kingdom of God, meaning goodness,

1443
00:57:58,420 --> 00:58:01,484
is right here, where it should be.

1444
00:58:01,519 --> 00:58:03,583
"I am what I am becoming."

1445
00:58:03,618 --> 00:58:05,184
That's what the Buddha brought in.

1446
00:58:05,219 --> 00:58:06,583
And that's what I taught.

1447
00:58:06,618 --> 00:58:09,584
But a talking snake
make a lady eat an apple,

1448
00:58:09,619 --> 00:58:10,715
So we're screwed.

1449
00:58:10,750 --> 00:58:12,282
Heaven and hell were peddled

1450
00:58:12,317 --> 00:58:15,567
so priests could rule
through seduction and terror,

1451
00:58:15,602 --> 00:58:18,817
save our souls that we never
lost in the first place.

1452
00:58:18,852 --> 00:58:20,449
I threw a clean pass...

1453
00:58:20,484 --> 00:58:22,584
they ran it out of the ballpark.

1454
00:58:22,619 --> 00:58:25,316
This is blasphemy.

1455
00:58:25,351 --> 00:58:28,167
It's horrible! Who else were you?

1456
00:58:28,202 --> 00:58:30,492
Solomon, Elvis, Jack the ripper?

1457
00:58:30,527 --> 00:58:32,605
It's been said that Buddha and Jesus

1458
00:58:32,640 --> 00:58:34,684
would laugh or cry if they'd known

1459
00:58:34,719 --> 00:58:36,115
what was done in their name.

1460
00:58:36,150 --> 00:58:37,950
And if there is a creator,

1461
00:58:37,985 --> 00:58:40,834
he'd probably feel the same way.

1462
00:58:40,869 --> 00:58:43,443
I see ceremony, ritual, processions,

1463
00:58:43,478 --> 00:58:46,147
genuflecting, moaning, intoning,

1464
00:58:46,182 --> 00:58:48,817
venerating cookies and wine,

1465
00:58:48,852 --> 00:58:50,583
and I think...

1466
00:58:50,618 --> 00:58:51,984
It's not what I had in mind.

1467
00:58:52,019 --> 00:58:53,316
But that's Vatican flapdoodle.

1468
00:58:53,351 --> 00:58:55,817
It doesn't have a thing to do with God.

1469
00:58:55,852 --> 00:58:59,001
As you said, John,
everywhere, religions...

1470
00:58:59,036 --> 00:59:02,150
from exalting life to
purging joy as a sin.

1471
00:59:02,185 --> 00:59:04,817
Rome does it as grand opera.

1472
00:59:06,084 --> 00:59:07,883
A simple path to goodness needs

1473
00:59:07,918 --> 00:59:09,850
a supernatural roadmap.

1474
00:59:09,885 --> 00:59:11,982
Supernatural...

1475
00:59:12,017 --> 00:59:14,649
A stupid word, I mean...

1476
00:59:14,684 --> 00:59:16,584
Anything that happens,
happens within nature,

1477
00:59:16,619 --> 00:59:18,718
whether we believe in it or not.

1478
00:59:18,753 --> 00:59:20,817
Like a 14,000-year-old caveman.

1479
00:59:29,651 --> 00:59:31,800
I- I-I drove for a while,

1480
00:59:31,835 --> 00:59:33,950
and then I sat for a while.

1481
00:59:33,985 --> 00:59:35,349
I'm so ashamed.

1482
00:59:35,384 --> 00:59:37,084
And I'm freezing.

1483
00:59:37,119 --> 00:59:38,349
Well, come inside.

1484
00:59:38,384 --> 00:59:40,517
I still don't believe you, of course.

1485
00:59:40,552 --> 00:59:41,549
You need help.

1486
00:59:41,584 --> 00:59:42,583
Everybody needs help.

1487
00:59:42,618 --> 00:59:44,684
Yes, well, some more than others.

1488
00:59:58,684 --> 01:00:00,848
From the Buddha to the cross,

1489
01:00:00,883 --> 01:00:05,551
I have always imagined
both as entirely mythic -

1490
01:00:05,586 --> 01:00:07,949
but I would like to hear more.

1491
01:00:07,984 --> 01:00:10,650
May I lie on the couch for a moment?

1492
01:00:10,685 --> 01:00:13,317
I'm not as young as I used to be.

1493
01:00:16,017 --> 01:00:17,049
Ohh!

1494
01:00:19,184 --> 01:00:23,216
So, you were Jesus.

1495
01:00:23,251 --> 01:00:26,351
Well, perhaps somebody had to
be, for better or for worse.

1496
01:00:26,386 --> 01:00:28,082
The jury is still out.

1497
01:00:28,117 --> 01:00:31,115
When did you begin to
believe you were Jesus?

1498
01:00:31,150 --> 01:00:34,251
When did you begin to believe
you were a psychiatrist?

1499
01:00:34,286 --> 01:00:37,349
Since I graduated Harvard medical school

1500
01:00:37,384 --> 01:00:40,084
and finished my residency,
I've had that feeling.

1501
01:00:40,119 --> 01:00:42,368
Oh, I sometimes dream about it.

1502
01:00:42,403 --> 01:00:44,583
Have you acted upon this belief?

1503
01:00:44,618 --> 01:00:46,984
I had a private practice for a while,

1504
01:00:47,019 --> 01:00:48,484
and then I taught.

1505
01:00:48,519 --> 01:00:49,915
Nothing unusual -

1506
01:00:49,950 --> 01:00:53,217
oh, until one day, I met a caveman

1507
01:00:53,252 --> 01:00:55,784
who thought he was Jesus.

1508
01:00:55,819 --> 01:00:58,282
Do you find that unusual?

1509
01:00:58,317 --> 01:01:00,750
Very. I would stake my reputation

1510
01:01:00,785 --> 01:01:03,149
he is as sane as I am,

1511
01:01:03,184 --> 01:01:06,117
so why does he persist in such a story?

1512
01:01:06,152 --> 01:01:08,284
There must be a reason, though.

1513
01:01:08,319 --> 01:01:10,184
Unless I imagined it all?

1514
01:01:10,219 --> 01:01:11,449
Is that possible?

1515
01:01:11,484 --> 01:01:13,317
I think you're as sane as he is.

1516
01:01:13,352 --> 01:01:15,067
Oh, God, I-

1517
01:01:15,102 --> 01:01:16,783
No.

1518
01:01:18,317 --> 01:01:21,251
Did you ever find it
prudent to worship yourself

1519
01:01:21,286 --> 01:01:23,050
rather than be thought a heretic?

1520
01:01:23,085 --> 01:01:24,282
That would be something.

1521
01:01:24,317 --> 01:01:26,850
Other times, Christianity
was considered heresy.

1522
01:01:26,885 --> 01:01:28,616
I had to pretend other faiths.

1523
01:01:28,651 --> 01:01:32,718
And what does Jesus have
to say to those present

1524
01:01:32,753 --> 01:01:35,117
who find it difficult to believe in him?

1525
01:01:35,152 --> 01:01:37,783
Believe in what he tried to teach,

1526
01:01:37,818 --> 01:01:39,715
without rigmarole.

1527
01:01:39,750 --> 01:01:42,433
Piety is not what the
lessons bring to people.

1528
01:01:42,468 --> 01:01:45,117
It's the mistake they
bring to the lessons.

1529
01:01:52,517 --> 01:01:55,251
Well, it's getting to be night.

1530
01:01:56,750 --> 01:01:58,917
I still have stuff to carry

1531
01:01:58,952 --> 01:02:01,284
and a long drive.

1532
01:02:01,319 --> 01:02:02,815
I'll help.

1533
01:02:02,850 --> 01:02:06,451
John, do you have
a destination in mind?

1534
01:02:07,817 --> 01:02:09,200
Never mind.

1535
01:02:09,235 --> 01:02:10,584
I won't ask.

1536
01:02:11,651 --> 01:02:12,651
Thank you.

1537
01:02:20,017 --> 01:02:22,848
Anyone mentally ill can imagine

1538
01:02:22,883 --> 01:02:25,850
a fantastic background,
even an entire life,

1539
01:02:25,885 --> 01:02:28,149
and sincerely believe it.

1540
01:02:28,184 --> 01:02:30,783
The man who thinks he is Napoleon

1541
01:02:30,818 --> 01:02:32,649
does believe it.

1542
01:02:32,684 --> 01:02:35,600
His true identity has taken a backseat

1543
01:02:35,635 --> 01:02:38,517
to his delusion and the need for it.

1544
01:02:38,552 --> 01:02:40,534
If that's the case with John,

1545
01:02:40,569 --> 01:02:42,517
there is a grave disorder.

1546
01:02:42,552 --> 01:02:44,949
Organized brilliantly.

1547
01:02:44,984 --> 01:02:47,049
He's got an answer for everything.

1548
01:02:47,084 --> 01:02:49,718
It might involve
rejection of his father,

1549
01:02:49,753 --> 01:02:51,401
of his entire early past,

1550
01:02:51,436 --> 01:02:53,015
replaced by this fantasy.

1551
01:02:53,050 --> 01:02:55,150
He says he can't remember his father.

1552
01:02:55,185 --> 01:02:56,149
Precisely why?

1553
01:02:56,184 --> 01:02:57,750
You said he was sane.

1554
01:02:57,785 --> 01:02:59,050
Did I?

1555
01:03:00,484 --> 01:03:02,950
Do you think that perhaps our caveman

1556
01:03:02,985 --> 01:03:04,750
has a monkey on his back?

1557
01:03:04,785 --> 01:03:06,349
Drugs?

1558
01:03:06,384 --> 01:03:07,848
No, no, no, no.

1559
01:03:07,883 --> 01:03:10,284
I've done a lot of consulting
work with narcotics.

1560
01:03:10,319 --> 01:03:12,401
I've seen people tripping, strung out--

1561
01:03:12,436 --> 01:03:14,484
Whatever's up with John, it isn't that.

1562
01:03:14,519 --> 01:03:16,368
I've looked for signs - none.

1563
01:03:16,403 --> 01:03:18,182
Could cavemen really talk?

1564
01:03:18,217 --> 01:03:20,618
We think that language
came into existence

1565
01:03:20,653 --> 01:03:21,882
60,000 years ago.

1566
01:03:21,917 --> 01:03:23,915
The structure of stone age culture

1567
01:03:23,950 --> 01:03:26,217
is evidence of the
ability to communicate -

1568
01:03:26,252 --> 01:03:27,616
verbally.

1569
01:03:29,352 --> 01:03:31,484
Oh, shut up.

1570
01:03:40,651 --> 01:03:42,850
Maybe it'd be easier if I were.

1571
01:03:42,885 --> 01:03:44,017
Crazy?

1572
01:03:45,284 --> 01:03:46,815
No.

1573
01:03:59,984 --> 01:04:02,715
That is fascinating, isn't it,

1574
01:04:02,750 --> 01:04:05,883
a brave attempt to teach
Buddhism in the west.

1575
01:04:05,918 --> 01:04:07,601
It's no wonder he failed.

1576
01:04:07,636 --> 01:04:09,249
We're not ready for it.

1577
01:04:09,284 --> 01:04:11,718
You're talking
as if you believed him.

1578
01:04:11,753 --> 01:04:13,885
Well, it is possible, isn't it?

1579
01:04:13,920 --> 01:04:15,901
I mean, anything is possible.

1580
01:04:15,936 --> 01:04:18,143
Look, we have two simple choices.

1581
01:04:18,178 --> 01:04:20,316
We can get all bent out of shape

1582
01:04:20,351 --> 01:04:22,718
intellectualizing or
bench-pressing logic,

1583
01:04:22,753 --> 01:04:25,351
or we can simply relax and enjoy it.

1584
01:04:25,386 --> 01:04:27,149
I can listen critically,

1585
01:04:27,184 --> 01:04:30,551
but I don't have to make
up my mind about anything.

1586
01:04:30,586 --> 01:04:32,015
But you think you do?

1587
01:04:32,050 --> 01:04:34,783
Well, unfortunately, there's
no authorities on prehistory,

1588
01:04:34,818 --> 01:04:36,549
so we couldn't stop him there.

1589
01:04:36,584 --> 01:04:38,384
There are experts on the Bible.

1590
01:04:38,419 --> 01:04:39,982
Dream on.

1591
01:04:40,017 --> 01:04:42,316
Yeah, thus the lost years of Jesus.

1592
01:04:42,351 --> 01:04:45,015
He didn't exist until John put on a hat.

1593
01:04:45,050 --> 01:04:49,084
I don't believe in angels and the
Nativity and the star in the east,

1594
01:04:49,119 --> 01:04:52,217
but there are stories about
the childhood of Jesus.

1595
01:04:52,252 --> 01:04:54,616
History hates a vacuum.

1596
01:04:54,651 --> 01:04:57,217
Improvisation, some of it very sincere,

1597
01:04:57,252 --> 01:04:58,349
fills the gaps.

1598
01:04:58,384 --> 01:04:59,715
It would have been easy

1599
01:04:59,750 --> 01:05:02,649
to falsify a past back then.

1600
01:05:02,684 --> 01:05:06,050
A few words, credulity...
time would do the rest.

1601
01:05:06,085 --> 01:05:08,182
Now you're talking as
if you believed him.

1602
01:05:08,217 --> 01:05:10,633
Well, look at the
popular myths surrounding

1603
01:05:10,668 --> 01:05:13,050
the Kennedy assassination
in a few short years.

1604
01:05:13,085 --> 01:05:16,084
You had, uh, conspiracy, mafia, CIA.

1605
01:05:16,119 --> 01:05:19,049
That's a mystique that'll never go away.

1606
01:05:19,084 --> 01:05:22,917
It's always been a small step
from a fallen leader to a god.

1607
01:05:22,952 --> 01:05:25,783
I don't think anybody
will deify Kennedy.

1608
01:05:25,818 --> 01:05:27,750
We're more sophisticated than that.

1609
01:05:27,785 --> 01:05:29,284
We are?

1610
01:05:29,319 --> 01:05:30,917
We are.

1611
01:05:34,517 --> 01:05:36,783
Well, you're finally fulfilling

1612
01:05:36,818 --> 01:05:39,050
one prophecy about the millennium, John.

1613
01:05:39,085 --> 01:05:40,984
What's that?

1614
01:05:41,019 --> 01:05:42,883
Here you are again.

1615
01:05:52,451 --> 01:05:54,416
You like the fire, John.

1616
01:05:54,451 --> 01:05:57,950
Everywhere I've lived,
I've had a fireplace.

1617
01:05:57,985 --> 01:06:00,451
Childhood fixation, I guess.

1618
01:06:02,117 --> 01:06:04,150
Helps me to feel secure.

1619
01:06:05,551 --> 01:06:07,618
There are predators out there.

1620
01:06:10,050 --> 01:06:11,867
One thing I didn't pack...

1621
01:06:11,902 --> 01:06:13,684
I thought I might need it.

1622
01:06:20,917 --> 01:06:24,217
<i>Wouldn't Sacre du printemps
be more appropriate?</i>

1623
01:06:24,252 --> 01:06:25,284
What?

1624
01:06:26,917 --> 01:06:28,982
You've got...

1625
01:06:29,017 --> 01:06:32,184
four men of science
completely baffled, my friend.

1626
01:06:32,219 --> 01:06:34,748
We-We don't know what to make of you.

1627
01:06:34,783 --> 01:06:37,516
Did you know Voltaire
was the first to suggest

1628
01:06:37,551 --> 01:06:40,984
that the universe was created
by a gigantic explosion?

1629
01:06:41,019 --> 01:06:43,282
I think Paul would agree.

1630
01:06:43,317 --> 01:06:45,748
And then Goethe was the first to suggest

1631
01:06:45,783 --> 01:06:49,651
that spiral nebulae were
swirling masses of stars.

1632
01:06:49,686 --> 01:06:51,815
We now call them galaxies.

1633
01:06:51,850 --> 01:06:54,549
It's kind of funny how
often new concepts of science

1634
01:06:54,584 --> 01:06:57,484
find their first tentative
forms of expression in the arts.

1635
01:06:57,519 --> 01:07:01,634
So did Beethoven do physics on the side?

1636
01:07:01,669 --> 01:07:05,750
He spent most of his
time lying on the floor

1637
01:07:05,785 --> 01:07:07,449
in front of his legless piano

1638
01:07:07,484 --> 01:07:10,217
surrounded by orange
peels and apple cores.

1639
01:07:12,384 --> 01:07:15,184
Now we're on the floor
listening to Beethoven.

1640
01:07:16,451 --> 01:07:17,982
Full circle.

1641
01:07:18,017 --> 01:07:20,317
Did you have, um...

1642
01:07:21,417 --> 01:07:23,115
any religious beliefs,

1643
01:07:23,150 --> 01:07:25,400
or did you give it much thought?

1644
01:07:25,435 --> 01:07:27,651
You can't get there with thought.

1645
01:07:27,686 --> 01:07:29,335
You have faith?

1646
01:07:29,370 --> 01:07:30,949
In a lot of things.

1647
01:07:30,984 --> 01:07:34,050
Do you have faith in
the future of the race?

1648
01:07:34,085 --> 01:07:36,015
I've seen species come and go.

1649
01:07:36,050 --> 01:07:38,117
Depends on their balance
with the environment.

1650
01:07:39,817 --> 01:07:41,517
We've made a mess of it.

1651
01:07:41,552 --> 01:07:43,234
There's still time,

1652
01:07:43,269 --> 01:07:44,882
if we use it well.

1653
01:07:44,917 --> 01:07:47,618
Christianity has been a worldwide belief

1654
01:07:47,653 --> 01:07:49,316
for 2,000 years.

1655
01:07:49,351 --> 01:07:51,551
How long did the Egyptians worship Isis

1656
01:07:51,586 --> 01:07:53,182
or the Sumerians Ishtar?

1657
01:07:53,217 --> 01:07:55,850
In India, sacred cows wandered freely

1658
01:07:55,885 --> 01:07:57,683
as reincarnated souls.

1659
01:07:57,718 --> 01:07:59,401
In a thousand years,
they'll be barbecued

1660
01:07:59,436 --> 01:08:01,084
and their souls will be in squirrels.

1661
01:08:01,119 --> 01:08:02,451
You weren't Jesus!

1662
01:08:04,484 --> 01:08:05,684
Oh, Edith.

1663
01:08:08,484 --> 01:08:11,251
If...it rains...
It won't.

1664
01:08:11,286 --> 01:08:12,635
How do you know that?

1665
01:08:12,670 --> 01:08:13,984
I don't smell it.

1666
01:08:17,451 --> 01:08:18,417
Were you...

1667
01:08:19,684 --> 01:08:21,950
I guess... a medicine man?

1668
01:08:21,985 --> 01:08:24,182
I was a shaman a few times.

1669
01:08:24,217 --> 01:08:27,551
I revealed some truths
to eat a little better.

1670
01:08:27,586 --> 01:08:30,618
You think that's all
religion is about...

1671
01:08:30,653 --> 01:08:33,182
selling hope and survival?

1672
01:08:33,217 --> 01:08:35,767
The Old Testament sells fear and guilt.

1673
01:08:35,802 --> 01:08:38,292
The New Testament is
a good code of ethics,

1674
01:08:38,327 --> 01:08:40,783
put into my mouth by
poets and philosophers

1675
01:08:40,818 --> 01:08:42,884
that are much smarter than I am.

1676
01:08:42,919 --> 01:08:44,950
The message is never practiced.

1677
01:08:46,117 --> 01:08:47,750
Fairy tales build churches.

1678
01:08:48,817 --> 01:08:50,967
What about the name "Jesus"?

1679
01:08:51,002 --> 01:08:53,117
Did you pull that out of a hat?

1680
01:08:53,152 --> 01:08:55,484
I called myself John.

1681
01:08:55,519 --> 01:08:57,782
I almost always do.

1682
01:08:57,817 --> 01:08:59,848
As tales of the resurrection spread,

1683
01:08:59,883 --> 01:09:02,651
<i>the name was confused
with the Hebrew "Yochanan,"</i>

1684
01:09:02,686 --> 01:09:04,501
Meaning "God is gracious."

1685
01:09:04,536 --> 01:09:06,282
My stay on Earth was seen

1686
01:09:06,317 --> 01:09:09,967
as divine proof of immortality.

1687
01:09:10,002 --> 01:09:13,618
That led to "God is salvation"

1688
01:09:13,653 --> 01:09:15,115
<i>or Hebrew "Yahshua,"</i>

1689
01:09:15,150 --> 01:09:18,317
which in translation
became my proper name,

1690
01:09:18,352 --> 01:09:20,951
<i>changing to late Greek, "Iesous,"</i>

1691
01:09:20,986 --> 01:09:23,516
<i>then to late Latin, "Iesus,"</i>

1692
01:09:23,551 --> 01:09:26,149
and finally medieval Latin, "Jesus,"

1693
01:09:26,184 --> 01:09:29,150
and it was a wonder
to watch it all happen.

1694
01:09:29,185 --> 01:09:32,301
Then you didn't claim
to be the son of God?

1695
01:09:32,336 --> 01:09:35,382
Began as a schoolhouse
and ended as a temple.

1696
01:09:35,417 --> 01:09:38,984
I said I had a master that
was greater than myself.

1697
01:09:39,019 --> 01:09:41,001
I never said he was my father.

1698
01:09:41,036 --> 01:09:42,949
I wanted to teach what I learned.

1699
01:09:42,984 --> 01:09:45,049
I never claimed to be king of the Jews,

1700
01:09:45,084 --> 01:09:48,217
I never walked on water,
I never raised the dead.

1701
01:09:48,252 --> 01:09:51,551
I never spoke of divine
except in the sense

1702
01:09:51,586 --> 01:09:53,718
of human goodness on Earth.

1703
01:09:57,251 --> 01:10:00,850
No wise men came from the
east to worship at a manger.

1704
01:10:00,885 --> 01:10:02,982
I did do a little healing

1705
01:10:03,017 --> 01:10:04,850
with some eastern medicine I'd learned.

1706
01:10:07,651 --> 01:10:08,750
That's it.

1707
01:10:12,551 --> 01:10:14,434
The three wise men began as a myth

1708
01:10:14,469 --> 01:10:16,317
about the birth of the Buddha.

1709
01:10:21,050 --> 01:10:25,017
John, I should be home,
uh, kissing my wife.

1710
01:10:27,217 --> 01:10:29,384
We're all here, trapped by your story...

1711
01:10:30,850 --> 01:10:36,618
hoping for a...
revolution? I don't know.

1712
01:10:39,950 --> 01:10:41,900
Are there any, uh...

1713
01:10:41,935 --> 01:10:43,850
more revelations for us?

1714
01:10:50,317 --> 01:10:52,217
It's just like old times.

1715
01:10:58,850 --> 01:11:00,817
You weren't Jesus.

1716
01:11:03,718 --> 01:11:06,017
Quote the sermon on the mount.

1717
01:11:06,052 --> 01:11:07,316
Which one?

1718
01:11:07,351 --> 01:11:10,551
Darby, King James,
new American standard?

1719
01:11:10,586 --> 01:11:12,416
Do you know them all?

1720
01:11:12,451 --> 01:11:15,618
No one knows the one, not even me.

1721
01:11:15,653 --> 01:11:16,949
I...

1722
01:11:16,984 --> 01:11:19,284
I did some teaching on a hill one day.

1723
01:11:19,319 --> 01:11:21,351
Not that many people stayed.

1724
01:11:21,386 --> 01:11:22,482
But you...

1725
01:11:22,517 --> 01:11:24,516
Biblical Jesus said,

1726
01:11:24,551 --> 01:11:26,984
"Who do you think I am?"

1727
01:11:27,019 --> 01:11:29,417
He gave them a choice.

1728
01:11:30,950 --> 01:11:32,317
I'm giving you one.

1729
01:11:35,284 --> 01:11:36,651
Were you?

1730
01:11:38,651 --> 01:11:41,284
If I said no, could you ever be sure?

1731
01:11:58,451 --> 01:12:00,384
Turn that off.

1732
01:12:00,419 --> 01:12:01,351
Please.

1733
01:12:04,451 --> 01:12:06,467
This has gone far enough.

1734
01:12:06,502 --> 01:12:08,449
It's gone much too far.

1735
01:12:08,484 --> 01:12:11,034
These people are very upset.

1736
01:12:11,069 --> 01:12:13,549
I don't believe you're mad,

1737
01:12:13,584 --> 01:12:15,883
But what you're saying is not true.

1738
01:12:16,984 --> 01:12:19,817
That leaves only one explanation.

1739
01:12:20,984 --> 01:12:23,084
The time has come when you must admit

1740
01:12:23,119 --> 01:12:24,284
this is a hoax...

1741
01:12:25,984 --> 01:12:27,249
A lie.

1742
01:12:27,284 --> 01:12:30,915
Isn't that true, John?

1743
01:12:30,950 --> 01:12:33,718
If you don't drop this now
- If you can -

1744
01:12:33,753 --> 01:12:35,249
I'll be convinced

1745
01:12:35,284 --> 01:12:38,234
that you need a great deal of attention.

1746
01:12:38,269 --> 01:12:41,184
I can have you committed
for observation.

1747
01:12:41,219 --> 01:12:42,851
You know that.

1748
01:12:42,886 --> 01:12:44,802
I ask you now

1749
01:12:44,837 --> 01:12:46,683
- I demand it -

1750
01:12:46,718 --> 01:12:49,783
that you tell these people the truth.

1751
01:12:49,818 --> 01:12:53,067
Give them closure.

1752
01:12:53,102 --> 01:12:56,317
It's time, John.

1753
01:12:56,352 --> 01:12:57,517
Please.

1754
01:13:11,184 --> 01:13:13,950
End of the line. Everybody off.

1755
01:13:17,217 --> 01:13:19,182
What?!

1756
01:13:19,217 --> 01:13:21,350
It was a story.

1757
01:13:21,385 --> 01:13:23,484
It was all a story.

1758
01:13:24,503 --> 01:13:25,417
Good God!

1759
01:13:27,217 --> 01:13:29,000
Another fairy tale?

1760
01:13:29,035 --> 01:13:30,748
All of it? But what--?

1761
01:13:30,783 --> 01:13:32,149
What in the name of heaven...?

1762
01:13:32,184 --> 01:13:34,417
John, you had us wondering
whether you were sane or not,

1763
01:13:34,452 --> 01:13:36,015
and it's just a story!

1764
01:13:36,050 --> 01:13:39,351
Where'd you come off with such
a half-baked, asinine idea?

1765
01:13:39,386 --> 01:13:41,150
At least you're relieved I'm not a nut.

1766
01:13:41,185 --> 01:13:42,818
I'd prefer you were!

1767
01:13:42,853 --> 01:13:44,451
You gave me the idea.

1768
01:13:44,486 --> 01:13:45,851
All of you.

1769
01:13:45,886 --> 01:13:47,182
Come again?

1770
01:13:47,217 --> 01:13:48,784
Edith saw my fake Van Gogh.

1771
01:13:48,819 --> 01:13:50,235
You could have just told me.

1772
01:13:50,270 --> 01:13:51,860
You commented that I never age.

1773
01:13:51,895 --> 01:13:53,451
You gave me the book on early man.

1774
01:13:53,486 --> 01:13:55,049
Dan, you spotted the burin

1775
01:13:55,084 --> 01:13:56,750
and you said, "if stones could speak."

1776
01:13:56,785 --> 01:13:58,382
I knew it.

1777
01:13:58,417 --> 01:14:00,848
I got the notion, I ran it past you

1778
01:14:00,883 --> 01:14:03,451
to check your reactions,
and I took it too far.

1779
01:14:03,486 --> 01:14:04,815
Too far?

1780
01:14:04,850 --> 01:14:06,316
Check my reaction.

1781
01:14:06,351 --> 01:14:08,917
You asked if I was a figure
from religious history,

1782
01:14:08,952 --> 01:14:10,434
if there were others like me,

1783
01:14:10,469 --> 01:14:11,882
if I'd created future identities.

1784
01:14:11,917 --> 01:14:15,067
We were chasing our
tails around the maypole,

1785
01:14:15,102 --> 01:14:18,217
enjoying the mystery,
the analytical stretch.

1786
01:14:18,252 --> 01:14:20,150
You were playing my game!

1787
01:14:20,185 --> 01:14:21,715
I was playing yours.

1788
01:14:21,750 --> 01:14:24,351
Oh, man, you know,
you had us going, right?

1789
01:14:24,386 --> 01:14:25,583
You were good, man.

1790
01:14:25,618 --> 01:14:27,082
You know those Chinese boxes,

1791
01:14:27,117 --> 01:14:30,184
one inside the other inside
the other inside the other?

1792
01:14:30,219 --> 01:14:33,251
I feel like I'm in the last box.

1793
01:14:33,286 --> 01:14:35,551
You son of a...

1794
01:14:35,586 --> 01:14:36,583
bitch!

1795
01:14:36,618 --> 01:14:38,150
How could you do this to us?

1796
01:14:38,185 --> 01:14:40,216
I was worried about you.

1797
01:14:40,251 --> 01:14:42,600
I know, I was tempted
to cop out many times,

1798
01:14:42,635 --> 01:14:44,950
But I couldn't resist
seeing whether or not

1799
01:14:44,985 --> 01:14:46,718
you could refute what I was saying.

1800
01:14:46,753 --> 01:14:48,652
I had the perfect audience.

1801
01:14:48,687 --> 01:14:50,551
Anthropologist, archaeologist,

1802
01:14:50,586 --> 01:14:52,651
Christian literalist...

1803
01:14:52,686 --> 01:14:54,815
a psychologist.

1804
01:14:54,850 --> 01:14:56,915
Okay, I've had enough of this.

1805
01:14:56,950 --> 01:14:59,017
I'm outta here.
You wanna come? Let's go.

1806
01:15:00,150 --> 01:15:01,382
So, John.

1807
01:15:01,417 --> 01:15:03,017
Are you gonna write the story?

1808
01:15:03,052 --> 01:15:04,651
If I do, I'll send you copies.

1809
01:15:04,686 --> 01:15:06,901
Don't bother with mine, okay?

1810
01:15:06,936 --> 01:15:09,117
You are absolutely certifiable.

1811
01:15:09,152 --> 01:15:10,850
I don't know you!

1812
01:15:13,217 --> 01:15:15,551
It was nice seeing
you again, Dr. Oldman.

1813
01:15:16,984 --> 01:15:18,783
Your name's a pun, isn't it?

1814
01:15:18,818 --> 01:15:19,783
Old man?

1815
01:15:21,651 --> 01:15:24,251
Did that help you with your story?

1816
01:15:24,286 --> 01:15:25,883
Linda!

1817
01:15:27,517 --> 01:15:28,584
Bye.

1818
01:15:32,050 --> 01:15:33,984
Well, Art was half right.

1819
01:15:35,553 --> 01:15:37,017
Which half?

1820
01:15:39,817 --> 01:15:42,817
Well, at least I don't
have to throw away half

1821
01:15:42,852 --> 01:15:44,618
of what I know about biology.

1822
01:15:44,653 --> 01:15:46,251
Which half?

1823
01:15:47,850 --> 01:15:49,915
It's a beautiful idea,

1824
01:15:49,950 --> 01:15:53,817
so rich, so full of possibilities.

1825
01:15:55,117 --> 01:15:57,184
Perhaps you should write
a paper on it, doctor.

1826
01:15:57,219 --> 01:15:58,915
Maybe I will.

1827
01:15:58,950 --> 01:16:01,117
I'll interview you in the rubber room

1828
01:16:01,152 --> 01:16:02,616
for further details.

1829
01:16:02,651 --> 01:16:04,684
You may still need help, my friend.

1830
01:16:18,217 --> 01:16:19,649
My ass.

1831
01:16:19,684 --> 01:16:21,848
I thought it sounded pretty good.

1832
01:16:21,883 --> 01:16:23,950
They believe you because they have to.

1833
01:16:23,985 --> 01:16:26,017
But the one thing that I know about you

1834
01:16:26,052 --> 01:16:27,583
is that you would never use people

1835
01:16:27,618 --> 01:16:29,351
or abuse their goodwill and intelligence

1836
01:16:29,386 --> 01:16:31,084
like they think you've
just done to them.

1837
01:16:31,119 --> 01:16:32,216
Psych 101?

1838
01:16:32,251 --> 01:16:34,815
No, it's woman,
one-on-one.

1839
01:16:34,850 --> 01:16:37,633
So you're a pretty fast liar, Mr. Ugg,

1840
01:16:37,668 --> 01:16:40,382
But I wanna know:
What's your real name?

1841
01:16:40,417 --> 01:16:45,351
Believe it or not, the
sound was always John.

1842
01:16:45,386 --> 01:16:47,285
Why'd you cave to Gruber?

1843
01:16:47,320 --> 01:16:48,952
What happened was enough.

1844
01:16:48,987 --> 01:16:50,549
Just- just needed to stop.

1845
01:16:50,584 --> 01:16:52,750
I shouldn't have expected it to work.

1846
01:16:54,150 --> 01:16:56,100
Fourteen thousand years old.

1847
01:16:56,135 --> 01:16:58,050
I bet that's a lot of women.

1848
01:16:58,085 --> 01:17:00,050
Are we counting?

1849
01:17:00,085 --> 01:17:01,417
Maybe.

1850
01:17:03,384 --> 01:17:05,451
Well, I'm taking Edith home.

1851
01:17:05,486 --> 01:17:06,384
Sandy?

1852
01:17:07,783 --> 01:17:09,317
I'm gonna stay.

1853
01:17:13,317 --> 01:17:16,050
Are you sorry for some
of those things you said?

1854
01:17:16,085 --> 01:17:18,618
I'm sorry I said them.

1855
01:17:18,653 --> 01:17:20,082
Well.

1856
01:17:20,117 --> 01:17:21,584
Like a good Christian,

1857
01:17:21,619 --> 01:17:24,783
I... oh, John.

1858
01:17:24,818 --> 01:17:26,584
Oh! Well.

1859
01:17:27,783 --> 01:17:30,015
You did a terrible thing,

1860
01:17:30,050 --> 01:17:32,449
but we're all so
thankful you're all right.

1861
01:17:32,484 --> 01:17:35,551
Even Art. He just hates
things he can't understand.

1862
01:17:35,586 --> 01:17:37,349
You're a sadist, John,

1863
01:17:37,384 --> 01:17:39,482
But I admit I got a kick out of

1864
01:17:39,517 --> 01:17:41,251
chasing my tail around your maypole...

1865
01:17:41,286 --> 01:17:43,451
Even if that is all I caught.

1866
01:17:43,486 --> 01:17:44,616
Good luck to you.

1867
01:17:44,651 --> 01:17:46,217
Wish you the best. Thank you.

1868
01:17:46,252 --> 01:17:47,251
Ready?

1869
01:17:56,284 --> 01:17:58,150
Later on.
Okay, good night.

1870
01:18:00,984 --> 01:18:01,917
Mm-hmm.

1871
01:18:05,317 --> 01:18:06,549
Mmm.

1872
01:18:06,584 --> 01:18:09,482
I don't know, man.

1873
01:18:09,517 --> 01:18:11,484
Something about this...

1874
01:18:11,519 --> 01:18:13,768
something about you, John.

1875
01:18:13,803 --> 01:18:15,982
The more I think about it,

1876
01:18:16,017 --> 01:18:18,883
the more I'm no longer
in that Chinese box.

1877
01:18:20,819 --> 01:18:22,616
I sense... space.

1878
01:18:22,651 --> 01:18:27,551
A kinda latitude of what
we happily call reality,

1879
01:18:27,586 --> 01:18:30,618
in which, as everybody keeps saying...

1880
01:18:31,950 --> 01:18:33,683
anything's possible.

1881
01:18:33,718 --> 01:18:35,584
Yes. No, no. No, no.

1882
01:18:35,619 --> 01:18:37,418
No. No more words.

1883
01:18:37,453 --> 01:18:39,182
I'm gonna go home,

1884
01:18:39,217 --> 01:18:41,017
<i>and I'm gonna watch Star Trek</i>

1885
01:18:41,052 --> 01:18:43,134
for a dose of sanity.

1886
01:18:43,169 --> 01:18:45,182
Good luck to you, man,

1887
01:18:45,217 --> 01:18:47,633
wherever this may lead you.

1888
01:18:47,668 --> 01:18:50,015
You drop me a line sometime.

1889
01:18:50,050 --> 01:18:51,883
Let me know how you're making out.

1890
01:18:53,451 --> 01:18:54,417
I will.

1891
01:19:05,917 --> 01:19:08,782
So, John Oldman.

1892
01:19:08,817 --> 01:19:11,384
What other pun names have you used?

1893
01:19:11,419 --> 01:19:12,718
Lots.

1894
01:19:14,251 --> 01:19:17,317
John Paley for John Paleolithic,

1895
01:19:17,352 --> 01:19:19,715
John Savage...

1896
01:19:19,750 --> 01:19:21,850
Got really crazy about 60 years ago,

1897
01:19:21,885 --> 01:19:23,718
when I was teaching at Harvard,

1898
01:19:23,753 --> 01:19:26,549
I was John Thomas Partee.

1899
01:19:26,584 --> 01:19:29,117
John T. Partee -
Boston tea party.

1900
01:19:29,152 --> 01:19:30,334
I get it.

1901
01:19:30,369 --> 01:19:31,576
Yeah, I know.

1902
01:19:31,611 --> 01:19:32,783
Wait, wait, wait.

1903
01:19:32,818 --> 01:19:35,115
Boston?

1904
01:19:35,150 --> 01:19:37,283
60 years ago?

1905
01:19:37,318 --> 01:19:39,417
J-John Partee?

1906
01:19:43,317 --> 01:19:47,883
You did not teach chemistry!
I do not believe you!

1907
01:19:49,117 --> 01:19:51,718
Your mother's name was Nola.

1908
01:19:51,753 --> 01:19:52,950
No. Yeah.

1909
01:19:52,985 --> 01:19:55,015
No.

1910
01:19:55,050 --> 01:19:57,516
Yes, Nola.

1911
01:19:57,551 --> 01:19:59,184
My mother!

1912
01:20:00,551 --> 01:20:02,150
I reject this!

1913
01:20:03,750 --> 01:20:05,750
My-My-My dog's name.

1914
01:20:06,850 --> 01:20:08,750
We had him before I was born.

1915
01:20:08,785 --> 01:20:09,782
Woofie.

1916
01:20:09,817 --> 01:20:11,150
Woof, woof, woofie...

1917
01:20:16,651 --> 01:20:18,601
Gruber. She remarried?

1918
01:20:18,636 --> 01:20:20,551
She said you abandoned us.

1919
01:20:21,618 --> 01:20:23,282
Sorry, I had to move on.

1920
01:20:23,317 --> 01:20:25,050
You know that. I left enough.

1921
01:20:25,085 --> 01:20:27,234
- I left enough.
- I'm cold.

1922
01:20:27,269 --> 01:20:29,360
Chilly Willy, always cold.

1923
01:20:29,395 --> 01:20:31,416
Never could stand the cold.

1924
01:20:31,451 --> 01:20:35,150
Wait, you-- you had a beard.

1925
01:20:35,185 --> 01:20:36,817
Yeah, you used to tug on it

1926
01:20:36,852 --> 01:20:38,384
to see if it was real.

1927
01:20:38,419 --> 01:20:39,950
Agh! Will!

1928
01:20:39,985 --> 01:20:40,883
God.

1929
01:20:42,317 --> 01:20:43,748
911, now!

1930
01:20:45,685 --> 01:20:47,517
Come on, Will.

1931
01:20:47,552 --> 01:20:48,683
Will.

1932
01:20:48,718 --> 01:20:49,651
Come on, buddy.

1933
01:21:21,850 --> 01:21:23,933
You'll stay in touch, Dr. Oldman,

1934
01:21:23,968 --> 01:21:26,076
in case there are any questions.

1935
01:21:26,111 --> 01:21:28,184
I'll be back for the funeral.

1936
01:21:28,219 --> 01:21:29,217
Miss.

1937
01:21:39,484 --> 01:21:41,651
You never saw a grown child die.

1938
01:21:43,117 --> 01:21:44,050
No.

